       = 7\n| nationalyears1 = 2012\n| nationalteam1  = [[Kazakhstan national under-17 football team|Kazakhstan U17]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 6\n| nationalgoals1 = 1\n| nationalyears2 = 2014\n| nationalteam2  = [[Kazakhstan national under-19 football team|Kazakhstan U19]]\n| nationalcaps2  = 3\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3 = 2015\u2013\n| nationalteam3  = [[Kazakhstan national under-21 football team|Kazakhstan U21]]\n| nationalcaps3  = 16\n| nationalgoals3 = 2\n| nationalyears4 = 2018\u2013\n| nationalteam4  = [[Kazakhstan national football team|Kazakhstan]]\n| nationalcaps4  = 13\n| nationalgoals4 = 1\n| pcupdate       = {{date|2019-11-10}}\n| ntupdate       = 19 November 2019\n}}\n\n'''Maxim Fedin''' ({{lang-kk|\u041c\u0430\u043a\u0441\u0438\u043c \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0438\u043d}}, born 8 June 1996) is a [[Kazakhstan|Kazakh]] [[Association football|football]] [[midfielder]] who plays for [[FC Tobol]] in the [[Kazakhstan Premier League]].\n\n==Career==\n===Club===\n====Bayterek Astana====\nFedin passed the youth school of [[FC Irtysh Pavlodar|Irtysh Pavlodar]]. For the [[2014 Kazakhstan First Division|2014]] season, he made 26 appearances and scored 3 goals, playing with [[FC Bayterek|Bayterek]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gradsubotica.co.rs/spartak-potpisao-kazahstanac-maksim-fedin/|title=Spartak: Potpisao Kazahstanac Maksim Fedin|website=gradsubotica.co.rs|language=Serbian|date=26 January 2015|accessdate=23 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Spartak Subotica====\nFedin joined [[FK Spartak Subotica|Spartak Subotica]] in January 2015, but he could not playing until the end of [[2014\u201315 Serbian SuperLiga|2014\u201315]] season, because of injury.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sports.kz/news/maksim-fedin-v-baytereke-ya-priobrel-neobhodimyiy-dlya-vyistupleniy-za-rubejom-opyit|title=\u041c\u0430\u043a\u0441\u0438\u043c \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0438\u043d: \"\u0412 \"\u0411\u0430\u0439\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043a\u0435\" \u044f \u043f\u0440\u0438\u043e\u0431\u0440\u0435\u043b \u043d\u0435\u043e\u0431\u0445\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043c\u044b\u0439 \u0434\u043b\u044f \u0432\u044b\u0441\u0442\u0443\u043f\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0437\u0430 \u0440\u0443\u0431\u0435\u0436\u043e\u043c \u043e\u043f\u044b\u0442\"|website=sports.kz|language=Kazakh|date=14 May 2015|accessdate=23 August 2015}}</ref> He made his [[Serbian SuperLiga|SuperLiga]] debut in the 7th fixture of [[2015\u201316 Serbian SuperLiga|2015\u201316]] season, against [[FK Metalac Gornji Milanovac|Metalac]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.superliga.rs/index.php/izvestaji-2015-16/2863-7-kolo-spartak-metalac#.Vdkm-iV_OqY|title=7.Kolo: Spartak - Metalac|website=Serbian SuperLiga official website|language=Serbian|date=22 August 2015|accessdate=23 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Atyrau====\nOn 9 July 2016, Fedin signed for [[Kazakhstan Premier League]] side [[FC Atyrau]].<ref>{{cite web|title=\u0424\u0435\u0434\u0438\u043d \u2013 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447\u043e\u043a \u0410\u0442\u044b\u0440\u0430\u0443|url=http://www.rfcatyrau.kz/rus/news/1466|website=rfcatyrau.kz|publisher=FC Atyrau|accessdate=9 July 2016|language=Russian|date=9 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Okzhetpes====\nOn 12 January 2017, Fedin signed a one-year contract with [[FC Okzhetpes]].<ref>{{cite web|title=\u0424\u0435\u0434\u0438\u043d \u2013 \u0438\u0433\u0440\u043e\u043a \u0424\u041a \u041e\u043a\u0436\u0435\u0442\u043f\u0435\u0441|url=http://www.okzhetpes.kz/ru/news/fedin-igrok-fk-okzhetpes|website=okzhetpes.kz/|publisher=FC Okzhetpes|accessdate=12 January 2017|language=Russian|date=12 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Tobol====\nOn 25 December 2018, [[FC Tobol]] announced the siging of Fedin,<ref>{{cite web|title=\u041d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430\u0439 \u041f\u0430\u043d\u0438\u043d: \u00ab\u0422\u043e\u0431\u043e\u043b\u00bb \u0433\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0432 \u043a \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0432\u044b\u043c \u0441\u0431\u043e\u0440\u0430\u043c \u2014 \u0441\u043e\u0445\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u043a\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044f\u043a, \u0441\u0444\u043e\u0440\u043c\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u0442\u0440\u0435\u043d\u0435\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0448\u0442\u0430\u0431|url=https://fctobol.kz/nikolaj-panin-tobol-gotov-k-pervym-sboram-sohranili-kostyak-sformirovali-trenerskij-shtab/|website=fctobol.kz|publisher=FC Tobol|accessdate=5 July 2018|language=Russian|date=25 December 2017}}</ref> with Fedin extending his contract with Tobol until the end of 2020 on 31 December 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0424\u0435\u0434\u0438\u043d \u0441 \u043d\u0430\u043c\u0438! |url=https://fctobol.kz/fedin-s-nami/ |website=fctobol.kz/ |publisher=FC Tobol |accessdate=5 January 2020 |language=Russian |date=31 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===International===\nMaxim Fedin was a regular member of all youth sections of the Kazakh national team, namely the [[Kazakhstan national under-17 football team|U17]], [[Kazakhstan national under-19 football team|U19]] and [[Kazakhstan national under-21 football team|U21]]. On June 10, 2017, he was part of the [[Kazakhstan national football team]] in a qualifying game for the 2018 FIFA World Cup against Denmark, but ended being an unused substitute.<ref>{{Soccerway|maxim-fedin/273270}}</ref> He received a new call for the friendly game against Azerbaijan played on June 5, 2018,<ref>[http://www.kff.kz/news/view/1527528089- KAZAKHSTAN NATIONAL TEAM SQUAD FOR MATCH WITH AZERBAIJAN] at KFF.kz, retrieved 5-6-2018</ref> but again failed to debut. He made his debut for the senior squad on 13 October 2018 in a [[2018\u201319 UEFA Nations League D]] game against [[Latvia national football team|Latvia]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[UEFA]]|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefanationsleague/season=2019/matches/round=2000959/match=2024060/index.html|title=Latvia v Kazakhstan game report|date=13 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|match played 10 November 2019}}<ref>{{cite web|title=M.Fedin|url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/maxim-fedin/273270/|website=soccerway.com|publisher=Soccerway|accessdate=6 July 2017}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|National Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Continental\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|valign=\"center\"|[[FK Spartak Subotica|Spartak Subotica]]\n|[[2015\u201316 Serbian SuperLiga|2015\u201316]]\n|valign=\"center\"|[[Serbian SuperLiga]]\n|5||0||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||colspan=\"2\"|-||6||0\n|-\n|valign=\"center\"|[[FC Atyrau|Atyrau]]\n|[[2016 FC Atyrau season|2016]]\n|valign=\"center\"|[[Kazakhstan Premier League]]\n|13||1||2||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||colspan=\"2\"|-||15||1\n|-\n|valign=\"center\"|[[FC Okzhetpes|Okzhetpes]]\n|[[2017 FC Okzhetpes season|2017]]\n|valign=\"center\"|[[Kazakhstan Premier League]]\n|26||2||2||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||colspan=\"2\"|-||28||3\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\" valign=\"center\"|[[FC Tobol|Tobol]]\n|[[2018 FC Tobol season|2018]]\n|rowspan=\"2\" valign=\"center\"|[[Kazakhstan Premier League]]\n|28||2||2||0||4||2||colspan=\"2\"|-||34||4\n|-\n|[[2019 FC Tobol season|2019]]\n|33||5||4||2||2||0||colspan=\"2\"|-||39||7\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!61!!7!!6!!2!!6!!2!!-!!-!!73!!11\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career total\n!105!!10!!11!!3!!6!!2!!-!!-!!122!!15\n|}\n\n===International===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!colspan=3|[[Kazakhstan national football team|Kazakhstan national team]]\n|-\n!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|2018||4||0\n|-\n|2019||8||1\n|-\n!Total||12||1\n|}\n''Statistics accurate as of match played 19 November 2019''<ref name=\"NFT Stats\">{{NFT player|pid=72205|name=Maksim Fedin|accessdate=20 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===International goals===\n:''Scores and results list Kazakhstan's goal tally first.''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! No. !! Date !! Venue !! Opponent !! Score !! Result !! Competition\n|-\n|align=center| 1. || 11 June 2019 || [[Astana Arena]], [[Nur-Sultan]], Kazakhstan || {{fb|SMR}} || align=center | '''2'''\u20130 || align=center | 4\u20130 || [[UEFA Euro 2020 qualifying Group I|UEFA Euro 2020 qualification]] \n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Soccerway|maxim-fedin/273270}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150704221200/http://www.utakmica.rs/fudbaler/1365-fedin-maksim Maxim Fedin stats] at utakmica.rs\n* {{FootballDatabase.eu|246713}}\n* {{UEFA player|250056129}}\n\n{{FC Tobol squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fedin, Maxim}}\n[[Category:1996 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Kazakhstani footballers]]\n[[Category:Kazakhstan under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Kazakhstan international footballers]]\n[[Category:FC Bayterek players]]\n[[Category:Kazakhstani expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Kazakhstani expatriate sportspeople in Serbia]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Serbia]]\n[[Category:FK Spartak Subotica players]]\n[[Category:Serbian SuperLiga players]]\n[[Category:FC Atyrau players]]\n[[Category:FC Tobol players]]\n[[Category:Kazakhstan Premier League players]]\n\n\n{{Kazakhstan-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "MrSimpleton16", "label": "safe", "comment": "Changed club", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maxim_Fedin"}
{"title_page": "Lyons-la-For\u00eat", "text_new": "{{Infobox French commune\n|name                   = Lyons-la-For\u00eat\n|commune status         = [[Communes of France|Commune]]\n|image                  = Lyons-la-For\u00eat.jpg\n|caption                = 17th-century covered market\n|image coat of arms     = Blason Lyons-la-For\u00eat.svg\n|arrondissement         = Les Andelys\n|canton                 = Romilly-sur-Andelle\n|INSEE                  = 27377\n|postal code            = 27480\n|mayor                  = Thierry Plouvier\n|term                   = 2008&ndash;2014\n|intercommunality       =\n|coordinates            = {{coord|49.4003|1.4769|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation m            = 163\n|elevation min m        = 67\n|elevation max m        = 178\n|area km2               = 26.99\n|population             = {{France metadata Wikidata|population_total}}\n|population date        = {{France metadata Wikidata|population_as_of}}\n|population footnotes   = {{France metadata Wikidata|population_footnotes}}\n}}{{Copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n'''Lyons-la-For\u00eat''' is a [[Communes of France|commune]] of the [[Eure]] [[Departments of France|department]], [[Haute Normandie]] in Northwest [[France]].\n\nLyons-la-Floret is well known within the region due to its architecture, which has been maintained since its founding in the 17th century. It is also a recognized distinct geophysical and geocultural entity that is the end of [[Vexin normand]], and the forest of Lyons. The area around the town and the border with [[Pays de Bray]] is known for its traditional [[bocage]] landscape of woods, orchards, and cattle pasture.\n\n==Geography==\nLyons-la-For\u00eat<ref>The city of [[Lyon]], in France too, is sometimes written ''Lyons'' in English as well, but the writing and the pronunciation of /s/ is the result of a confusion with Lyons-la-For\u00eat. Lyon does not share the same etymology and is a former ''Lugdunu(m)'' that evolved step by step into Lyon.</ref> is located {{convert|34|km|mi|abbr=on}} from [[Rouen]] and {{convert|28|km|mi|abbr=on}} from [[Gisors]].\nFormer name: '''Saint-Denis-en-Lyons'''.\n\nLyons was originally the name of the forest < ''Licontio-/Ligontio-'', based probably on the Celtic root ''lic''/''lig'', that is also found in the name of the stream: la Lieure < ''Licoris /Ligoris''. Same root as the [[River Loire]] < ''Liger'' and ''-ley'' in [[Beverley]] ([[Yorkshire]]) from Celtic {{lang|cel|*bibro}} {{lang|cel|*licos}} > Old English {{lang|ang|beofor}} beaver, {{lang|ang|*licc}} stream.\n\n==History==\nAn early mention of a ducal residence in Lyons can be found in 936, when [[William I, Duke of Normandy]] used to stay.\n\nThe [[Ch\u00e2teau de Lyons-la-For\u00eat|castle of Lyons-la-For\u00eat]] was constructed at the start of the 12th century by [[Henry I of England]], also known as \"Henri Beauclerc\".<ref name=MinCult>Ministry of Culture: [http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/merimee_fr?ACTION=RETROUVER&REQ=((IA00016912):REF) Ch\u00e2teau fort] {{in lang|fr}}</ref> He died there in 1135, supposedly from \"a surfeit of [[lampreys]]\".<ref>Judith A. Green ''Henry I: King of England and Duke of Normandy'', Cambridge University Press</ref>\n\nThe town and the castle were occupied by King [[Philip II Augustus]] of France in 1193 but the following year, [[Richard I of England]], back from captivity, obtained the restitution of Lyons; the king of England and Duke of Normandy stayed frequently until 1198. In 1202, Philip II Augustus re-conquered the city, and after him, several French kings were attracted by the Lyons forest and the good hunting grounds.\n\nFrom 1359 to 1398, the castellan domain of Lyons was part of [[Blanche d'\u00c9vreux|Blanche de Navarre]]'s [[dower]] after she became the widow of King [[Philip VI of France]]. In 1403-1422,  it was the dower of [[Isabeau de Bavi\u00e8re]], wife of king [[Charles VI of France|Charles]]. In 1419, in the course of the [[Hundred Years' War]], the English took Lyons.<ref name = communes>[http://www.communes-francaises.com/27/lyons-la-foret/ Site listing] the [[communes of France]].</ref>\n\nDuring the second World War, the area was used for parachute drops of agents [[F. F. E. Yeo-Thomas]] and [[Andr\u00e9 Dewavrin]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Marshall |first1=Bruce |title=The White Rabbit |publisher=PAN |page=29 }}</ref>\n\n==Population==\n{{Historical populations\n|align=left\n| 1793| 1650\n| 1800| 1674\n| 1806| 1754\n| 1821| 1660\n| 1831| 1650\n| 1836| 1608\n| 1841| 1524\n| 1846| 1538\n| 1851| 1609\n| 1856| 1441\n| 1861| 1443\n| 1866| 1391\n| 1872| 1370\n| 1876| 1323\n| 1881| 1269\n| 1886| 1260\n| 1891| 1223\n| 1896| 1185\n| 1901| 1157\n| 1906| 1042\n| 1911| 1000\n| 1921| 931\n| 1926| 856\n| 1931| 818\n| 1936| 792\n| 1946| 878\n| 1954| 781\n| 1962| 749\n| 1968| 880\n| 1975| 772\n| 1982| 734\n| 1990| 701\n| 1999| 795\n| 2008| 754\n| 2012| 744\n}}\n{{clear-left}}\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Normandie Eure Lyons1 tango7174.jpg|Normandy style houses\nFile:Normandie Eure Lyons2 tango7174.jpg|[[Maurice Ravel]]'s mansion\nFile:Vestiges de l'enceinte fortifi\u00e9e.JPG|Remains of the rampart\n</gallery>\n\n==Sights==\n\n* Gallo-Roman theatre (private property)\n* Castle of [[Henry I of England]] (private property)\n* Covered market place (18th century)\n* Church Saint-Denis (12th and 18th centuries)\n* Town hall (17th century)\n* Houses built in typical [[Normandy#Architecture|Normandy style]] (17th and 18th centuries)\n* The [[forest]] is 10,700 [[hectare]]s, the largest state forest in [[Normandy]] and one of the largest [[Beech]] [[forest]]s in Europe. It is renowned for the \"cathedral-like\" straightness and height of its trees' trunks. One of its characteristics is its having so many open spaces and [[Glade (geography)|clearings]] among which lie small villages and hamlets. This makes a transition between the [[Vexin]] plateau and the [[Andelle]] valley.<ref name=\"tourismoff\">[http://www.lyons.tourisme.free.fr/ Lyons Tourism office].</ref>\n\n==Personalities==\n\n* [[Henry I of England]] died on 1 December 1135 of [[Foodborne illness|food poisoning]] from eating \"a surfeit of [[lamprey]]s\" (of which he was excessively fond) at Lyons-la-For\u00eat (then Saint-Denis-en-Lyons). The [[mucus]] and [[Serum (blood)|serum]] of several lamprey species, including the [[Caspian lamprey]] (''Caspiomyzon wagneri''), river lampreys (''Lampetra fluviatilis'' and ''L. planeri''), and sea lamprey (''Petromyzon marinus''), are known to be toxic and require thorough cleaning before cooking and consumption.<ref>{{FishBase species |genus=Lampetra |species=fluviatilis |month=September |year=2012}} (citing {{cite book|first1=Pamela |last1=Bristow |title=The Illustrated Encyclopedia of Fishes |publisher=Chancellor Press |location=London |date=30 April 1992 |isbn=9781851521364 }}).</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Mk-IdNTTJB0C&lpg=PA695&dq=%22Lampetra%20fluviatilis%22%20toxic&pg=PA695#v=onepage&q=%22Lampetra%20fluviatilis%22%20toxic&f=false |first=S. S. |last=Deshpande |date=29 Aug 2002 |title=Handbook of Food Toxicology |page=695 |publisher=CRC Press |isbn=978-0824707606}}</ref>\n\n*Lyons-la-For\u00eat was the birthplace of [[Enguerrand de Marigny]] (1260&ndash;1315), [[Grand Chamberlain of France|chamberlain]] and minister of [[Philip IV of France|Philip IV the Fair]].\n*It was also the birthplace of [[Isaac de Benserade]], French poet (1612\u20131691), who was one of the first intellectuals in France to evoke female homosexuality in a theater play.\n*[[Maurice Ravel]] stayed in Lyons many times from 1917 to 1922. He wrote music including ''[[Le tombeau de Couperin]]'' in Le Fresne, one of the old mansions of Lyons-la-For\u00eat.<ref name=\"leclos\">[http://www.leclosduquesnay.fr/villes.htm info site on the Pays de Bray.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081112224524/http://www.leclosduquesnay.fr/villes.htm |date=2008-11-12 }}</ref>\n*[[Monique de La Bruchollerie]] (1915 \u2013 1972),the classical concert pianist, lived there all her life with her family.\n*[[G\u00e9rard Souzay]] (1918 \u2013 2004), the French [[baritone]], lived there for a while during the [[Second World War]], at la Fontaineresse, on the banks of the Lieure.\n*[[\u00c9mile-Jacques Ruhlmann]] (1879 \u2013 1933) was a renowned French designer of furniture and interiors. His house is described in several publications concerning his life and work.\n*The artist [[Paul-\u00c9mile Pissarro]] (the youngest son of [[Camille Pissarro]]) lived here for some years from 1922, when he bought a house and had the garden designed by his godfather, [[Claude Monet]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Communes of the Eure department]]\n\n==References==\n*[http://www.insee.fr/en/home/home_page.asp INSEE]\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Lyons-la-For\u00eat}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061101144003/http://www.paris-normandie.com/dossiers/ciel/27Eure/Lyonslaforet/IndexLyonsForet.htm Aerial pictures of Lyons-la-For\u00eat]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081111122631/http://lyonslaforet.free.fr/ Pictures \u2013 Some of the town's cultural traits].\n\n{{Eure communes}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lyonslaforet}}\n[[Category:Communes of Eure]]\n[[Category:Plus Beaux Villages de France]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox French commune\n|name                   = Lyons-la-For\u00eat\n|commune status         = [[Communes of France|Commune]]\n|image                  = Lyons-la-For\u00eat.jpg\n|caption                = 17th-century covered market\n|image coat of arms     = Blason Lyons-la-For\u00eat.svg\n|arrondissement         = Les Andelys\n|canton                 = Romilly-sur-Andelle\n|INSEE                  = 27377\n|postal code            = 27480\n|mayor                  = Thierry Plouvier\n|term                   = 2008&ndash;2014\n|intercommunality       =\n|coordinates            = {{coord|49.4003|1.4769|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation m            = 163\n|elevation min m        = 67\n|elevation max m        = 178\n|area km2               = 26.99\n|population             = {{France metadata Wikidata|population_total}}\n|population date        = {{France metadata Wikidata|population_as_of}}\n|population footnotes   = {{France metadata Wikidata|population_footnotes}}\n}}{{Copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n'''Lyons-la-For\u00eat''' is a [[Communes of France|commune]] of the [[Eure]] [[Departments of France|department]], [[Haute Normandie]] in Northwest [[France]].\n\nLyons-la-Floret is well known within the region due to its architecture, which has been maintained since its founding in the 17th century. It is also a recognized distinct geophysical and geocultural entity that is the end of [[Vexin normand]], and the forest of Lyons. The area around the town and the border with [[Pays de Bray]] is known for its traditional [[bocage]] landscape of woods, orchards, and cattle pasture.\n\n==Geography==\nLyons-la-For\u00eat<ref>The city of [[Lyon]], in France too, is sometimes written ''Lyons'' in English as well, but the writing and the pronunciation of /s/ is the result of a confusion with Lyons-la-For\u00eat. Lyon does not share the same etymology and is a former ''Lugdunu(m)'' that evolved step by step into Lyon.</ref> is located {{convert|34|km|mi|abbr=on}} from [[Rouen]] and {{convert|28|km|mi|abbr=on}} from [[Gisors]].\nFormer name: '''Saint-Denis-en-Lyons'''.\n\nLyons was originally the name of the forest < ''Licontio-/Ligontio-'', based probably on the Celtic root ''lic''/''lig'', that is also found in the name of the stream: la Lieure < ''Licoris /Ligoris''. Same root as the [[River Loire]] < ''Liger'' and ''-ley'' in [[Beverley]] ([[Yorkshire]]) from Celtic {{lang|cel|*bibro}} {{lang|cel|*licos}} > Old English {{lang|ang|beofor}} beaver, {{lang|ang|*licc}} stream.\n\n==History==\nAn early mention of a ducal residence in Lyons can be found in 936, when [[William I, Duke of Normandy]] used to stay.\n\nThe [[Ch\u00e2teau de Lyons-la-For\u00eat|castle of Lyons-la-For\u00eat]] was constructed at the start of the 12th century by [[Henry I of England]], also known as \"Henri Beauclerc\".<ref name=MinCult>Ministry of Culture: [http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/merimee_fr?ACTION=RETROUVER&REQ=((IA00016912):REF) Ch\u00e2teau fort] {{in lang|fr}}</ref> He died there in 1135, supposedly from \"a surfeit of [[lampreys]]\".<ref>Judith A. Green ''Henry I: King of England and Duke of Normandy'', Cambridge University Press</ref>\n\nThe town and the castle were occupied by King [[Philip II Augustus]] of France in 1193 but the following year, [[Richard I of England]], back from captivity, obtained the restitution of Lyons; the king of England and Duke of Normandy stayed frequently until 1198. In 1202, Philip II Augustus re-conquered the city, and after him, several French kings were attracted by the Lyons forest and the good hunting grounds.\n\nFrom 1359 to 1398, the castellan domain of Lyons was part of [[Blanche d'\u00c9vreux|Blanche de Navarre]]'s [[dower]] after she became the widow of King [[Philip VI of France]]. In 1403-1422,  it was the dower of [[Isabeau de Bavi\u00e8re]], wife of king [[Charles VI of France|Charles]]. In 1419, in the course of the [[Hundred Years' War]], the English took Lyons.<ref name = communes>[http://www.communes-francaises.com/27/lyons-la-foret/ Site listing] the [[communes of France]].</ref>\n\nDuring the second World War, the area was used for parachute drops of agents [[F. F. E. Yeo-Thomas]] and [[Andr\u00e9 Dewavrin]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Marshall |first1=Bruce |title=The White Rabbit |publisher=PAN |page=29 }}</ref>\n\n==Population==\n{{Historical populations\n|align=left\n| 1793| 1650\n| 1800| 1674\n| 1806| 1754\n| 1821| 1660\n| 1831| 1650\n| 1836| 1608\n| 1841| 1524\n| 1846| 1538\n| 1851| 1609\n| 1856| 1441\n| 1861| 1443\n| 1866| 1391\n| 1872| 1370\n| 1876| 1323\n| 1881| 1269\n| 1886| 1260\n| 1891| 1223\n| 1896| 1185\n| 1901| 1157\n| 1906| 1042\n| 1911| 1000\n| 1921| 931\n| 1926| 856\n| 1931| 818\n| 1936| 792\n| 1946| 878\n| 1954| 781\n| 1962| 749\n| 1968| 880\n| 1975| 772\n| 1982| 734\n| 1990| 701\n| 1999| 795\n| 2008| 754\n| 2012| 744\n}}\n{{clear-left}}\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Normandie Eure Lyons1 tango7174.jpg|Normandy style houses\nFile:Normandie Eure Lyons2 tango7174.jpg|[[Maurice Ravel]]'s mansion\nFile:Vestiges de l'enceinte fortifi\u00e9e.JPG|Remains of the rampart\n</gallery>\n\n==Sights==\n\n* Gallo-Roman theatre (private property)\n* Castle of [[Henry I of England]] (private property)\n* Covered market place (18th century)\n* Church Saint-Denis (12th and 18th centuries)\n* Town hall (17th century)\n* Houses built in typical [[Normandy#Architecture|Normandy style]] (17th and 18th centuries)\n* The [[forest]] is 10,700 [[hectare]]s, the largest state forest in [[Normandy]] and one of the largest [[Beech]] [[forest]]s in Europe. It is renowned for the \"cathedral-like\" straightness and height of its trees' trunks. One of its characteristics is its having so many open spaces and [[Glade (geography)|clearings]] among which lie small villages and hamlets. This makes a transition between the [[Vexin]] plateau and the [[Andelle]] valley.<ref name=\"tourismoff\">[http://www.lyons.tourisme.free.fr/ Lyons Tourism office].</ref>\n\n==Personalities==\n\n* [[Henry I of England]] died on 1 December 1135 of [[Foodborne illness|food poisoning]] from eating \"a surfeit of [[lamprey]]s\" (of which he was excessively fond) at Lyons-la-For\u00eat (then Saint-Denis-en-Lyons). The [[mucus]] and [[Serum (blood)|serum]] of several lamprey species, including the [[Caspian lamprey]] (''Caspiomyzon wagneri''), river lampreys (''Lampetra fluviatilis'' and ''L. planeri''), and sea lamprey (''Petromyzon marinus''), are known to be toxic, and require thorough cleaning before cooking and consumption.<ref>{{FishBase species |genus=Lampetra |species=fluviatilis |month=September |year=2012}} (citing {{cite book|first1=Pamela |last1=Bristow |title=The Illustrated Encyclopedia of Fishes |publisher=Chancellor Press |location=London |date=30 April 1992 |isbn=9781851521364 }}).</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Mk-IdNTTJB0C&lpg=PA695&dq=%22Lampetra%20fluviatilis%22%20toxic&pg=PA695#v=onepage&q=%22Lampetra%20fluviatilis%22%20toxic&f=false |first=S. S. |last=Deshpande |date=29 Aug 2002 |title=Handbook of Food Toxicology |page=695 |publisher=CRC Press |isbn=978-0824707606}}</ref>\n\n*Lyons-la-For\u00eat was the birthplace of [[Enguerrand de Marigny]] (1260&ndash;1315), [[Grand Chamberlain of France|chamberlain]] and minister of [[Philip IV of France|Philip IV the Fair]].\n*It was also the birthplace of [[Isaac de Benserade]], French poet (1612\u20131691), who was one of the first intellectuals in France to evoke female homosexuality in a theater play.\n*[[Maurice Ravel]] stayed in Lyons many times from 1917 to 1922. He wrote music including ''[[Le tombeau de Couperin]]'' in Le Fresne, one of the old mansions of Lyons-la-For\u00eat.<ref name=\"leclos\">[http://www.leclosduquesnay.fr/villes.htm info site on the Pays de Bray.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081112224524/http://www.leclosduquesnay.fr/villes.htm |date=2008-11-12 }}</ref>\n*[[Monique de La Bruchollerie]] (1915 \u2013 1972),the classical concert pianist, lived there all her life with her family.\n*[[G\u00e9rard Souzay]] (1918 \u2013 2004), the French [[baritone]], lived there for a while during the [[Second World War]], at la Fontaineresse, on the banks of the Lieure.\n*[[\u00c9mile-Jacques Ruhlmann]] (1879 \u2013 1933) was a renowned French designer of furniture and interiors. His house is described in several publications concerning his life and work.\n*The artist [[Paul-\u00c9mile Pissarro]] (the youngest son of [[Camille Pissarro]]) lived here for some years from 1922, when he bought a house and had the garden designed by his godfather, [[Claude Monet]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Communes of the Eure department]]\n\n==References==\n*[http://www.insee.fr/en/home/home_page.asp INSEE]\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Lyons-la-For\u00eat}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061101144003/http://www.paris-normandie.com/dossiers/ciel/27Eure/Lyonslaforet/IndexLyonsForet.htm Aerial pictures of Lyons-la-For\u00eat]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081111122631/http://lyonslaforet.free.fr/ Pictures \u2013 Some of the town's cultural traits].\n\n{{Eure communes}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lyonslaforet}}\n[[Category:Communes of Eure]]\n[[Category:Plus Beaux Villages de France]]\n", "name_user": "Temple29", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lyons-la-For%C3%AAt"}
{"title_page": "\u1e0c\u0101d", "text_new": "{{short description|Letter of the Arabic alphabet}}\n'''{{transl|ar|DIN|\u1e0c\u0101d}}''' ({{lang|ar|\ufebd}}), is one of the six letters the [[Arabic alphabet]] added to the twenty-two inherited from the [[Phoenician alphabet]] (the others being {{transl|ar|DIN|[[\u1e6f\u0101\u02be]]}}, {{transl|ar|DIN|[[\u1e2b\u0101\u02be]]}}, {{transl|ar|DIN|[[\u1e0f\u0101l]]}}, {{transl|ar|DIN|[[\u1e93\u0101\u02be]]}}, {{transl|ar|DIN|[[ghain|\u0121ayn]]}}). In name and shape, it is a variant of {{transl|ar|DIN|[[tsade|\u1e63\u0101d]]}}.\nIts numerical value is 800 (see [[Abjad numerals]]).\n\nThe sound it represented at the time of the introduction of the Arabic alphabet is somewhat uncertain, likely a [[pharyngealization|pharyngealized]] [[voiced alveolar lateral fricative]] {{audio-IPA|Voiced pharyngealized alveolar lateral fricative.ogg|[\u026e\u02e4]}} or a similar [[affricate]]d sound {{IPAblink|d\u0361\u026e|d\u0361\u026e\u02e4}} or {{IPAblink|d\u0361\u026e|d\u02e1\u02e4}}.<ref name=Versteegh1999/> \nIn contemporary Arabic, it may represent a [[pharyngealization|pharyngealized]] [[voiced alveolar stop]] {{audio-IPA|Voiced_pharyngealized_alveolar_stop.ogg|[d\u02e4]}}, pharyngealized voiced dental stop {{IPAblink|d\u032a|d\u032a\u02e4}} or [[velarization|velarized]] voiced dental stop {{IPAblink|d\u032a|d\u032a\u02e0}}.<ref name=Versteegh1997/>\n\n{{Arabic alphabet shapes|\u0636}}\n\n==Origin==\nBased on ancient descriptions of this sound, it is clear that in [[Classical Arabic|Qur'anic Arabic]] ''\u1e0d'' was some sort of unusual [[lateral consonant|lateral]] sound.<ref name=Versteegh1997/><ref name=Versteegh1999/><ref name=Versteegh2000/><ref name=Ferguson1959/><ref name=Ferguson1997/> [[Sibawayh]], author of the first book on [[Arabic grammar]], explained the letter as being articulated from \"between the first part of the side of the tongue and the adjoining [[Molar (tooth)|molars]]\". It is reconstructed by modern linguists as having been either a [[pharyngealization|pharyngealized]] [[voiced alveolar lateral fricative]] {{audio-IPA|Voiced pharyngealized alveolar lateral fricative.ogg|[\u026e\u02e4]}} or a similar [[affricate]]d sound {{IPAblink|d\u0361\u026e|d\u0361\u026e\u02e4}} or {{IPAblink|d\u0361\u026e|d\u02e1\u02e4}}.<ref name=Versteegh1999/><ref name=Versteegh2000/> The affricated form is suggested by loans of ''\u1e0d'' into Akkadian as ''ld'' or ''l\u1e6d'' and into Malaysian as ''dl''.<ref name=\"Versteegh1997\" /> However, not all linguists agree on this; the French orientalist Andr\u00e9 Roman supposes that the letter was actually a voiced emphatic alveolo-palatal sibilant {{IPAslink|\u0291|\u0291\u02e4}}, similar to the Polish ''[[\u017a]]''.<ref name=Versteegh1999/><ref name=Versteegh2000/><ref name=Roman1983/>\n\nThis is an extremely unusual sound, and led the early Arabic grammarians to describe Arabic as the {{lang|ar|\u0644\u063a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0636\u0627\u062f}} ''lughat a\u1e0d-\u1e0d\u0101d'' \"the language of the ''\u1e0d\u0101d''\", since the sound was thought to be unique to Arabic.<ref name=\"Versteegh1997\" /> \nThe emphatic lateral nature of this sound is possibly inherited from [[Proto-Semitic]], and is compared to a phoneme in [[South Semitic]] languages such as [[Mehri language|Mehri]] (where it is usually an [[ejective consonant|ejective]] [[lateral fricative]]). \nThe corresponding letter in the  [[South Arabian alphabet]] is [[File:himjar za2.PNG|14px|\u1e0d]] {{transl|sem|\u1e63\u0301}}, and in [[Ge'ez alphabet]]  '''{{transl|sem|\u1e62\u0301appa}}''' <span style=\"font-size:140%;\">\u1340</span>), although in [[Ge'ez language|Ge'ez]] it merged early on with ''{{transl|sem|\u1e63}}.'' \n\nThe reconstruction of [[Proto-Semitic language|Proto-Semitic]] phonology includes an emphatic [[voiceless alveolar lateral fricative]] {{IPAblink|\u026c|\u026c\u02bc}} or [[Ejective alveolar lateral affricate|affricate]] {{IPAblink|t\u026c|t\u0361\u026c\u02bc}} for ''{{transl|sem|\u1e63\u0301}}''. This sound is considered to be the direct ancestor of Arabic ''{{transl|ar|DIN|\u1e0d\u0101d}}'', while merging with {{transl|sem|\u1e63\u0101d}} in most other [[Semitic languages]].\n\nThe letter itself is distinguished a derivation, by addition of a [[Arabic diacritics|diacritic dot]], from [[\u0635]] ''\u1e63\u0101d'' (representing /s\u02e4/).\n\n==Pronunciation==\n[[File:The_main_Pronunciations_of_written_\u0636_in_Arabic_dialects.png|thumb|The main pronunciations of written {{angbr|{{lang|ar|\u0636}}}} in Arabic dialects.|500x500px]]\nThe standard pronunciation of this letter in modern [[Standard Arabic]] is the \"[[emphatic consonant|emphatic]]\" {{IPA|/d/}}: [[pharyngealization|pharyngealized]] [[voiced alveolar stop]] {{audio-IPA|Voiced_pharyngealized_alveolar_stop.ogg|[d\u02e4]}}, pharyngealized voiced dental stop {{IPAblink|d\u032a|d\u032a\u02e4}} or [[velarization|velarized]] voiced dental stop {{IPAblink|d\u032a|d\u032a\u02e0}}.<ref name=Versteegh1997/>\n\nIn most Bedouin influenced Arabic vernaculars {{lang|ar|\u0636}} ''\u1e0d\u0101d'' and {{lang|ar|\u0638}} ''[[\u1e93\u0101\u02be]]'' have been merged quite early.<ref name=Versteegh1999/> like in the varieties (such as [[Bedouin Arabic|Bedouin]] and [[Mesopotamian Arabic|Iraqi]]), where the dental fricatives are preserved, both the letters are pronounced {{IPA|/\u00f0\u02e4/}}.<ref name=Versteegh1999/><ref name=Versteegh2000/><ref name=Ferguson1997/> However, there are dialects in South Arabia and in [[Hassaniya Arabic|Mauritania]] where both the letters are kept different but not in all contexts.<ref name=Versteegh1999/> In other vernaculars such as Egyptian the distinction between {{lang|ar|\u0636}} ''\u1e0d\u0101d'' and {{lang|ar|\u0638}} ''[[\u1e93\u0101\u02be]]'' is most of the time made; but Classical Arabic ''\u1e93\u0101\u02be'' often becomes {{IPA|/z\u02e4/}}, e.g. ''\u02bfa\u1e93\u012bm'' (< Classical {{lang|ar|\u0639\u0638\u064a\u0645}} ''\u02bfa\u1e0f\u0323\u012bm'') \"great\".<ref name=Versteegh1999/><ref name=Versteegh2000/><ref name=\"Rets\u00f62012\"/>\n\n\"De-emphaticized\" pronunciation of the both letters in the form of the plain {{IPA|/z/}} entered into other non-Arabic languages such as Persian, Urdu, Turkish.<ref name=Versteegh1999/> However, there do exist Arabic borrowings into [[Ibero-Romance languages]] as well as Hausa and Malay, where ''\u1e0d\u0101d'' and ''\u1e93\u0101\u02be'' are differentiated.<ref name=Versteegh1999/>\n\n==Transliteration==\n{{lang|ar|\u0636}} is transliterated as ''\u1e0d'' ([[D]] with [[dot (diacritic)|underdot]]) in [[romanization of Arabic|romanization]]. The combination \u27e8dh\u27e9 is also sometimes used colloquially. In varieties where the \u1e0c\u0101d has merged with the [[\u1e92\u0101\u02be]], the symbol for the latter might be used for both (eg. \u27e8{{lang|ar|\u0638\u0644}}\u27e9 'to stay' and \u27e8{{lang|ar|\u0636\u0644}}\u27e9 'to be lost' may both be transcribed as {{lang|ar-Latn|\u1e0f\u0323al}} in [[Gulf Arabic]]).\n\nWhen transliterating Arabic in the Hebrew alphabet,  it is either written as {{Hebrew|[[\u05d3]]}} (the letter for {{IPAslink|d}}) or as [[Romanization of Hebrew#\u0641\u063a\u063aTable|{{Hebrew|\u05e6\u05f3}}]] (''[[tsadi]]'' with [[geresh]]), which is also used to represent the /t\u0283/ sound.\n\n==Unicode==\n\n{{charmap\n|0636|name1=Arabic Letter Dad\n}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Arabic phonology]]\n*{{transl|sem|[[Sat (letter)|Sat]]}}\n*{{transl|sem|[[\u015aawt]]}}\n*{{transl|ar|DIN|[[\u1e0c]]}}\n\n==References==\n<references>\n<ref name=Ferguson1959>{{cite journal|last1=Ferguson|first1=Charles|title=The Arabic koine|journal=Language|date=1959|volume=35|issue=4|page=630|doi=10.2307/410601|url=}}</ref>\n<ref name=Ferguson1997>{{cite book|last1=Ferguson|first1=Charles Albert|editor1-last=Belnap|editor1-first=R. Kirk|editor2-last=Haeri|editor2-first=Niloofar|title=Structuralist studies in Arabic linguistics: Charles A. Ferguson's papers, 1954\u20131994|date=1997|orig-year=1959|publisher=Brill|isbn=9004105115|pages=67\u201368|chapter=The Arabic koine|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=l03h94vqCQMC&pg=PA67}}</ref>\n<ref name=Roman1983>{{cite book|last1=Roman|first1=Andr\u00e9|title=\u00c9tude de la phonologie et de la morphologie de la koin\u00e9 arabe|date=1983|publisher=Universit\u00e9 de Provence|location=Aix-en-Provence|volume=1|pages=162\u2013206}}</ref>\n<ref name=Versteegh1997>{{cite book|last1=Versteegh|first1=Kees|title=The Arabic language|date=2003|orig-year=1997|publisher=Edinburgh University Press|location=Edinburgh|isbn=9780748614363|page=89|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OHfse3YY6NAC&pg=PA89|edition=Repr.}}</ref>\n<ref name=Versteegh1999>{{cite book|last1=Versteegh|first1=Kees|editor1-last=Arazi|editor1-first=Albert|editor2-last=Sadan|editor2-first=Joseph|editor3-last=Wasserstein|editor3-first=David J.|title=Compilation and Creation in Adab and Lu\u0121a: Studies in Memory of Naphtali Kinberg (1948\u20131997)|date=1999|pages=273\u2013286|chapter=Loanwords from Arabic and the merger of \u1e0d/\u1e0f\u0323 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hNNHi_RdJ1MC&pg=PA273}}</ref>\n<ref name=Versteegh2000>{{cite book|last1=Versteegh|first1=Kees|editor1-last=Kinberg|editor1-first=Leah|editor2-last=Versteegh|editor2-first=Kees|title=Studies in the Linguistic Structure of Classical Arabic|date=2000|publisher=Brill|isbn=9004117652|pages=197\u2013199|chapter=Treatise on the pronunciation of the ''\u1e0d\u0101d''|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_EJ861jo4AQC&pg=PA197}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Rets\u00f62012\">{{cite book|last=Rets\u00f6|first=Jan|editor-last=Weninger|editor-first=Stefan|title=The Semitic Languages: An International Handbook|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SMzgBLT87MkC&pg=PA786|year=2012|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|isbn=978-3-11-025158-6|pages=785\u2013786|chapter=Classical Arabic}}</ref>\n</references>\n\n{{Arabic language}}\n{{Northwest Semitic abjad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dad}}\n[[Category:Arabic letters]]\n[[Category:Ge'ez language]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Letter of the Arabic alphabet}}\n'''{{transl|ar|DIN|\u1e0c\u0101d}}''' ({{lang|ar|\ufebd}}), is one of the six letters the [[Arabic alphabet]] added to the twenty-two inherited from the [[Phoenician alphabet]] (the others being {{transl|ar|DIN|[[\u1e6f\u0101\u02be]]}}, {{transl|ar|DIN|[[\u1e2b\u0101\u02be]]}}, {{transl|ar|DIN|[[\u1e0f\u0101l]]}}, {{transl|ar|DIN|[[\u1e93\u0101\u02be]]}}, {{transl|ar|DIN|[[ghain|\u0121ayn]]}}). In name and shape, it is a variant of {{transl|ar|DIN|[[tsade|\u1e63\u0101d]]}}.\nIts numerical value is 800 (see [[Abjad numerals]]).\n\nThe sound it represented at the time of the introduction of the Arabic alphabet is somewhat uncertain, likely a [[pharyngealization|pharyngealized]] [[voiced alveolar lateral fricative]] {{audio-IPA|Voiced pharyngealized alveolar lateral fricative.ogg|[\u026e\u02e4]}} or a similar [[affricate]]d sound {{IPAblink|d\u0361\u026e|d\u0361\u026e\u02e4}} or {{IPAblink|d\u0361\u026e|d\u02e1\u02e4}}.<ref name=Versteegh1999/> \nIn contemporary Arabic, it may represent a [[pharyngealization|pharyngealized]] [[voiced alveolar stop]] {{audio-IPA|Voiced_pharyngealized_alveolar_stop.ogg|[d\u02e4]}}, pharyngealized voiced dental stop {{IPAblink|d\u032a|d\u032a\u02e4}} or [[velarization|velarized]] voiced dental stop {{IPAblink|d\u032a|d\u032a\u02e0}}.<ref name=Versteegh1997/>\n\n{{Arabic alphabet shapes|\u0636}}\n\n==Origin==\nBased on ancient descriptions of this sound, it is clear that in [[Classical Arabic|Qur'anic Arabic]] ''\u1e0d'' was some sort of unusual [[lateral consonant|lateral]] sound.<ref name=Versteegh1997/><ref name=Versteegh1999/><ref name=Versteegh2000/><ref name=Ferguson1959/><ref name=Ferguson1997/> [[Sibawayh]], author of the first book on [[Arabic grammar]], explained the letter as being articulated from \"between the first part of the side of the tongue and the adjoining [[Molar (tooth)|molars]]\". It is reconstructed by modern linguists as having been either a [[pharyngealization|pharyngealized]] [[voiced alveolar lateral fricative]] {{audio-IPA|Voiced pharyngealized alveolar lateral fricative.ogg|[\u026e\u02e4]}} or a similar [[affricate]]d sound {{IPAblink|d\u0361\u026e|d\u0361\u026e\u02e4}} or {{IPAblink|d\u0361\u026e|d\u02e1\u02e4}}.<ref name=Versteegh1999/><ref name=Versteegh2000/> The affricated form is suggested by loans of ''\u1e0d'' into Akkadian as ''ld'' or ''l\u1e6d'' and into Malaysian as ''dl''.<ref name=\"Versteegh1997\" /> However, not all linguists agree on this; the French orientalist Andr\u00e9 Roman supposes that the letter was actually a voiced emphatic alveolo-palatal sibilant {{IPAslink|\u0291|\u0291\u02e4}}, similar to the Polish ''[[\u017a]]''.<ref name=Versteegh1999/><ref name=Versteegh2000/><ref name=Roman1983/>\n\nThis is an extremely unusual sound, and led the early Arabic grammarians to describe Arabic as the {{lang|ar|\u0644\u063a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0636\u0627\u062f}} ''lughat a\u1e0d-\u1e0d\u0101d'' \"the language of the ''\u1e0d\u0101d''\", since the sound was thought to be unique to Arabic.<ref name=\"Versteegh1997\" /> \nThe emphatic lateral nature of this sound is possibly inherited from [[Proto-Semitic]], and is compared to a phoneme in [[South Semitic]] languages such as [[Mehri language|Mehri]] (where it is usually an [[ejective consonant|ejective]] [[lateral fricative]]). \nThe corresponding letter in the  [[South Arabian alphabet]] is [[File:himjar za2.PNG|14px|\u1e0d]] {{transl|sem|\u1e63\u0301}}, and in [[Ge'ez alphabet]]  '''{{transl|sem|\u1e62\u0301appa}}''' <span style=\"font-size:140%;\">\u1340</span>), although in [[Ge'ez language|Ge'ez]] it merged early on with ''{{transl|sem|\u1e63}}.'' \n\nThe reconstruction of [[Proto-Semitic language|Proto-Semitic]] phonology includes an emphatic [[voiceless alveolar lateral fricative]] {{IPAblink|\u026c|\u026c\u02bc}} or [[Ejective alveolar lateral affricate|affricate]] {{IPAblink|t\u026c|t\u0361\u026c\u02bc}} for ''{{transl|sem|\u1e63\u0301}}''. This sound is considered to be the direct ancestor of Arabic ''{{transl|ar|DIN|\u1e0d\u0101d}}'', while merging with {{transl|sem|\u1e63\u0101d}} in most other [[Semitic languages]].\n\nThe letter itself is distinguished a derivation, by addition of a [[Arabic diacritics|diacritic dot]], from [[\u0635]] ''\u1e63\u0101d'' (representing /s\u02e4/).\n\n==Pronunciation==\n[[File:The_main_Pronunciations_of_written_\u0636_in_Arabic_dialects.png|thumb|The main pronunciations of written {{angbr|{{lang|ar|\u0636}}}} in Arabic dialects.|500x500px]]\nThe standard pronunciation of this letter in modern [[Standard Arabic]] is the \"[[emphatic consonant|emphatic]]\" {{IPA|/d/}}: [[pharyngealization|pharyngealized]] [[voiced alveolar stop]] {{audio-IPA|Voiced_pharyngealized_alveolar_stop.ogg|[d\u02e4]}}, pharyngealized voiced dental stop {{IPAblink|d\u032a|d\u032a\u02e4}} or [[velarization|velarized]] voiced dental stop {{IPAblink|d\u032a|d\u032a\u02e0}}.<ref name=Versteegh1997/>\n\nIn most Bedouin influenced Arabic vernaculars {{lang|ar|\u0636}} ''\u1e0d\u0101d'' and {{lang|ar|\u0638}} ''[[\u1e93\u0101\u02be]]'' have been merged quite early.<ref name=Versteegh1999/> like in the varieties (such as [[Bedouin Arabic|Bedouin]] and [[Mesopotamian Arabic|Iraqi]]), where the dental fricatives are preserved, both the letters are pronounced {{IPA|/\u00f0\u02e4/}}.<ref name=Versteegh1999/><ref name=Versteegh2000/><ref name=Ferguson1997/> However, there are dialects in South Arabia and in [[Hassaniya Arabic|Mauritania]] where both the letters are kept different but not in all contexts.<ref name=Versteegh1999/> In other vernaculars such as Egyptian the distinction between {{lang|ar|\u0636}} ''\u1e0d\u0101d'' and {{lang|ar|\u0638}} ''[[\u1e93\u0101\u02be]]'' is most of the time made; but Classical Arabic ''\u1e93\u0101\u02be'' often becomes {{IPA|/z\u02e4/}}, e.g. ''\u02bfa\u1e93\u012bm'' (< Classical {{lang|ar|\u0639\u0638\u064a\u0645}} ''\u02bfa\u1e0f\u0323\u012bm'') \"great\".<ref name=Versteegh1999/><ref name=Versteegh2000/><ref name=\"Rets\u00f62012\"/>\n\n\"De-emphaticized\" pronunciation of the both letters in the form of the plain {{IPA|/z/}} entered into other non-Arabic languages such as Persian, Urdu, Turkish.<ref name=Versteegh1999/> However, there do exist Arabic borrowings into [[Ibero-Romance languages]] as well as Hausa and Malay, where ''\u1e0d\u0101d'' and ''\u1e93\u0101\u02be'' are differentiated.<ref name=Versteegh1999/>\n\n==Transliteration==\n{{lang|ar|\u0636}} is transliterated as ''\u1e0d'' ([[D]] with [[dot (diacritic)|underdot]]) in [[romanization of Arabic|romanization]]. The combination <dh> is also sometimes used colloquially. In varieties where the \u1e0c\u0101d has merged with the [[\u1e92\u0101\u02be]], the symbol for the latter might be used for both (eg. <\u0638\u0644> 'to stay' and <\u0636\u0644> 'to be lost' may both be transcribed as ''\u1e0f\u0323al'' in [[Gulf Arabic]]).\n\nWhen transliterating Arabic in the Hebrew alphabet,  it is either written as {{Hebrew|[[\u05d3]]}} (the letter for {{IPAslink|d}}) or as [[Romanization of Hebrew#\u0641\u063a\u063aTable|{{Hebrew|\u05e6\u05f3}}]] (''[[tsadi]]'' with [[geresh]]), which is also used to represent the /t\u0283/ sound.\n\n==Unicode==\n\n{{charmap\n|0636|name1=Arabic Letter Dad\n}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Arabic phonology]]\n*{{transl|sem|[[Sat (letter)|Sat]]}}\n*{{transl|sem|[[\u015aawt]]}}\n*{{transl|ar|DIN|[[\u1e0c]]}}\n\n==References==\n<references>\n<ref name=Ferguson1959>{{cite journal|last1=Ferguson|first1=Charles|title=The Arabic koine|journal=Language|date=1959|volume=35|issue=4|page=630|doi=10.2307/410601|url=}}</ref>\n<ref name=Ferguson1997>{{cite book|last1=Ferguson|first1=Charles Albert|editor1-last=Belnap|editor1-first=R. Kirk|editor2-last=Haeri|editor2-first=Niloofar|title=Structuralist studies in Arabic linguistics: Charles A. Ferguson's papers, 1954\u20131994|date=1997|orig-year=1959|publisher=Brill|isbn=9004105115|pages=67\u201368|chapter=The Arabic koine|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=l03h94vqCQMC&pg=PA67}}</ref>\n<ref name=Roman1983>{{cite book|last1=Roman|first1=Andr\u00e9|title=\u00c9tude de la phonologie et de la morphologie de la koin\u00e9 arabe|date=1983|publisher=Universit\u00e9 de Provence|location=Aix-en-Provence|volume=1|pages=162\u2013206}}</ref>\n<ref name=Versteegh1997>{{cite book|last1=Versteegh|first1=Kees|title=The Arabic language|date=2003|orig-year=1997|publisher=Edinburgh University Press|location=Edinburgh|isbn=9780748614363|page=89|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OHfse3YY6NAC&pg=PA89|edition=Repr.}}</ref>\n<ref name=Versteegh1999>{{cite book|last1=Versteegh|first1=Kees|editor1-last=Arazi|editor1-first=Albert|editor2-last=Sadan|editor2-first=Joseph|editor3-last=Wasserstein|editor3-first=David J.|title=Compilation and Creation in Adab and Lu\u0121a: Studies in Memory of Naphtali Kinberg (1948\u20131997)|date=1999|pages=273\u2013286|chapter=Loanwords from Arabic and the merger of \u1e0d/\u1e0f\u0323 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hNNHi_RdJ1MC&pg=PA273}}</ref>\n<ref name=Versteegh2000>{{cite book|last1=Versteegh|first1=Kees|editor1-last=Kinberg|editor1-first=Leah|editor2-last=Versteegh|editor2-first=Kees|title=Studies in the Linguistic Structure of Classical Arabic|date=2000|publisher=Brill|isbn=9004117652|pages=197\u2013199|chapter=Treatise on the pronunciation of the ''\u1e0d\u0101d''|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_EJ861jo4AQC&pg=PA197}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Rets\u00f62012\">{{cite book|last=Rets\u00f6|first=Jan|editor-last=Weninger|editor-first=Stefan|title=The Semitic Languages: An International Handbook|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SMzgBLT87MkC&pg=PA786|year=2012|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|isbn=978-3-11-025158-6|pages=785\u2013786|chapter=Classical Arabic}}</ref>\n</references>\n\n{{Arabic language}}\n{{Northwest Semitic abjad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dad}}\n[[Category:Arabic letters]]\n[[Category:Ge'ez language]]\n", "name_user": "OwenBlacker", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTransliteration:Angle brackets;language tagging", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E1%B8%8C%C4%81d"}
{"title_page": "2003 Carolina Dodge Dealers 400", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{NASCAR race season infobox\n| Type           = CUST\n| Description    = Race 5 of 36 in the [[2003 NASCAR Winston Cup Series]] season\n| Race Name      = Carolina Dodge Dealers 400\n| Details ref    = <ref name=\"event\"/><ref name=RR400>{{cite web|title=2003 Carolina Dodge Dealers 400|url=https://www.racing-reference.info/race/2003_Carolina_Dodge_Dealers_400/W|publisher=Racing-Reference|accessdate=September 11, 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171101071449/http://racing-reference.info/race/2003_Carolina_Dodge_Dealers_400/W|archive-date=November 1, 2017}}</ref>\n| Fulldate       = {{Start date|2003|March|16}}\n| Year           = 2003\n| Race_No        = 5\n| Season_No      = 36\n| Image          = 2003 Carolina Dodge Dealers 400 finish.jpg\n| Caption       = The [[photo finish]] between [[Ricky Craven]] and [[Kurt Busch]]\n| Official name  = Carolina Dodge Dealers 400\n| Location       = [[Darlington Raceway]], [[Darlington, South Carolina]]\n| Course_mi      = 1.366\n| Course_km      = 2.198\n| Distance_laps  = 293\n| Distance_mi    = 400.238\n| Distance_km    = 644.014\n| Avg            = {{convert|126.214|mph|abbr=on}}\n| Weather        = Temperatures reaching up to {{convert|64.4|F|C}}; wind speeds up to {{convert|11.1|mph|km/h}}<ref name=WeatherInfo>{{cite web|title=Weather Information for Darlington, South Carolina|url=http://www.almanac.com/weather/history/SC/Darlington/2003-03-16|publisher=[[Old Farmer's Almanac]]|accessdate=September 11, 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180108062356/https://www.almanac.com/weather/history/SC/Darlington/2003-03-16|archive-date=January 8, 2018}}</ref>\n| Pole_Driver    = [[Elliott Sadler]]\n| Pole_Team      = [[Yates Racing|Robert Yates Racing]]\n| Pole_Time  = 28.902\n| Most_Driver    = [[Dale Earnhardt Jr.]]\n| Most_Team      = [[Dale Earnhardt, Inc.]]\n| Most_laps      = 91\n| Car            = 32\n| First_Driver   = [[Ricky Craven]]\n| First_Team     = [[PPI Motorsports]]\n| Network        = [[Fox NASCAR|Fox Broadcasting Company]]\n| Announcers     = [[Mike Joy]], [[Darrell Waltrip]], [[Larry McReynolds]]\n| Ratings = {{Plainlist|\n* 5.9/15 (Final)\n* 5.5/13 (Overnight)<ref>{{cite web|title=2003 NASCAR Winston Cup Series TV Ratings|url=http://www.jayski.com/pages/tvratings2003.htm|publisher=Jayski's Silly Season Site|accessdate=December 22, 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050207192126/http://www.jayski.com/pages/tvratings2003.htm|archivedate=February 7, 2005}}</ref>}}\n| Radio          = [[Motor Racing Network]]\n| Booth_Ann      = Joe Moore and [[Barney Hall]]\n| Turn_Ann       = [[Dave Moody]] (1 & 2) and [[Mike Bagley]] (3 & 4)\n|Course=|Attendance=55,000}}\n\nThe '''2003 Carolina Dodge Dealers 400''' was the fifth [[Stock car racing|stock car race]] of the [[2003 NASCAR Winston Cup Series]]. It was held on March 16, 2003, before a crowd of 55,000, in [[Darlington, South Carolina]], at [[Darlington Raceway]]. The 293-lap race, the 100th NASCAR Cup Series event at Darlington Raceway, was won by [[PPI Motorsports]] driver [[Ricky Craven]] after he started from the 31st position. [[Kurt Busch]] of the [[Roush Fenway Racing|Roush Racing]] squad finished in second place and [[Dave Blaney]] third for the [[Jasper Motorsports]] team.\n\n[[Elliott Sadler]] won the pole position by recording the fastest lap in qualifying. He and [[Ryan Newman (racing driver)|Ryan Newman]] traded the lead for the first two laps. [[Dale Earnhardt Jr.]] assumed the lead on lap 17 and went on to lead for 91 laps, more than any other driver. On lap 197, [[Jeff Gordon]] led at a [[Rolling start|rolling restart]] after a [[Racing flags#Yellow flag|yellow caution flag]], ahead of Sadler. Busch passed Gordon on the 269th lap but later had a [[power steering]] failure, allowing Craven to gradually lower his lead. By lap 291, Craven drew close enough to challenge Busch; after two attempts at a pass failed, he overtook Busch on the final lap, and won by two-thousands of a second, tied for the closest finish in series history.\n\nIt was Craven's second win of his career. The result advanced him from sixteenth to fifth in the [[List of NASCAR Sprint Cup Series champions|Drivers' Championship]], 143 [[List of NASCAR points scoring systems|points]] behind [[Matt Kenseth]], whose eighth-place finished  maintained his championship lead over [[Tony Stewart]]. [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]] maintained its lead in the [[List of NASCAR Manufacturers' champions|Manufacturers' Championship]], five points ahead of [[Chevrolet]] in second. [[Pontiac]] overtook [[Dodge]] for third with 31 races remaining in the season.\n\n==Background==\n[[File:DarlingtonRacewayDodgeCharger500.JPG|left|thumb|[[Darlington Raceway]] ''(pictured in 2008)'', where the race was held.]]\nThe 2003 Carolina Dodge Dealers 400 was the 5th of the 36 [[Stock car racing|stock car races]] in the [[2003 NASCAR Winston Cup Series]]. It was held on March 16, 2003, in [[Darlington, South Carolina]], at [[Darlington Raceway]],<ref name=\"RR400\" />  an [[Oval track racing|intermediate oval track]] which began hosting NASCAR races in the [[1950 NASCAR Grand National Series|1950 Grand National Series]];<ref name=DarlingtonTrack>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=4UC_C-0PQzoC&pg=PA10&lpg=PA10&dq=Darlington+Raceway+1950+intermediate+NASCAR&source=bl&ots=bn_ltdhDJo&sig=ACfU3U1RRr3cPVdtDXBYLTHx16vaW3YQMw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiE6PXay8rkAhVeQEEAHa4UCoIQ6AEwGnoECAsQAQ#v=onepage&q=Darlington%20Raceway%201950%20intermediate%20NASCAR&f=false|title=The Greatest NASCAR Tracks|last=Robinson|first=Matthew|publisher=[[Rosen Publishing]]|date=15 January 2005|isbn=978-1-4042-1400-2|location=New York City, United States|pages=10|access-date=September 12, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and was the 100th Cup Series race held at the track.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.indystar.com/print/articles/3/028832-3923-036.html|title=Darlington's 100th race may be its last in spring|last=Ballard|first=Steve|date=March 14, 2003|work=[[Indianapolis Star]]|access-date=September 12, 2019|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030314212215/http://www.indystar.com/print/articles/3/028832-3923-036.html|archive-date=March 14, 2003}}</ref> The track is a four-turn {{convert|1.366|mi|km|abbr=on}} egg-shaped superspeedway.<ref name=DarlingtonTrack/> Its first two turns are [[Banked turn|banked]] at 25 [[Degree (angle)|degrees]], while the final two turns are banked at 23 degrees. The [[Straight (racing)|frontstretch]] (the location of the finish line) and the backstretch are banked at three and two degrees, respectively.<ref name=\"darlingtontrackinfo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/jayski/tracks/story/_/id/18670465/darlington-raceway|title=Darlington Raceway|publisher=[[ESPN]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170628000656/http://www.espn.co.uk/jayski/tracks/story/_/id/18670465/darlington-raceway|archivedate=June 28, 2017|accessdate=January 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\nBefore the race, [[Matt Kenseth]] led the [[List of Monster Energy NASCAR Cup Series champions|Drivers' Championship]] with 618 [[List of NASCAR points scoring systems|points]], and [[Tony Stewart]] followed with 569 points. [[Michael Waltrip]] and [[Jimmie Johnson]] were third and fourth with 543 and 519 points respectively, ahead of [[Bobby Labonte]] in fifth with 510 points. [[Johnny Benson Jr.]], [[Kevin Harvick]], [[Jeff Gordon]], [[Jeff Burton]] and [[Dale Earnhardt Jr.]] rounded out the top ten.<ref name=PreRacePoints>{{cite web|url=http://jayski.com/stats/2003standings/mar9.htm|title=Drivers' Championship Classification After Atlanta|publisher=Jayski's Silly Season Site|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050307164708/http://jayski.com/stats/2003standings/mar9.htm|archivedate=March 7, 2005|accessdate=January 21, 2015}}</ref> In the [[List of NASCAR Manufacturers' champions|Manufacturers' Championship]], [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]] led with a total of 30 points, three points ahead of [[Chevrolet]] in second position. [[Dodge]], with 16 points, were one point ahead of [[Pontiac]] in third position.<ref name=Manufacturers>{{cite web|url=http://www.jayski.com/stats/2003/manu2003.htm|title=Manufacturers' Championship Classification|publisher=Jayski's Silly Season Site|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050204084345/http://www.jayski.com/stats/2003/manu2003.htm|archive-date=February 4, 2005|accessdate=January 21, 2015}}</ref> [[Sterling Marlin]] was the race's defending champion.<ref name=SIPreview>{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/motorsports/news/2003/03/12/glance_darlington_ap/|title='Still too tough to tame': Gordon looks to maintain momentum at Darlington|last=Austin|first=Chad|date=March 13, 2003|website=[[Sports Illustrated]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030422123139/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/motorsports/news/2003/03/12/glance_darlington_ap/|archive-date=April 22, 2003|accessdate=September 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDarlington Raceway had a highly abrasive track surface, which was heavily used and altered the complex of racing there. Drivers were required to strenuously monitor their tire degradation, and track position was the most important aspect due to the difficulty of on-circuit overtaking.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/rpm/wc/2003/0313/1522990.html|title=Difficult Darlington full of history|last=Massaro|first=Mike|date=March 13, 2003|publisher=ESPN|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030628114234/http://espn.go.com/rpm/wc/2003/0313/1522990.html|archive-date=June 28, 2003|access-date=September 12, 2019}}</ref> Gordon, who arrived as a favourite to win at Darlington Raceway due to his record six Cup Series victories there,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://foxsports.lycos.com/content/view?contentId=953444|title=Fox Watch: Five who thrive at Darlington|last=Behrendt|first=Todd|date=March 12, 2003|publisher=[[Fox Sports (United States)|Fox Sports]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030428233131/http://foxsports.lycos.com/content/view?contentId=953444|archive-date=April 28, 2003|access-date=September 12, 2019}}</ref> expressed a desire to continue his good form at the track: \"We didn't win in Atlanta, but we led laps and battled hard for the win. That was our first good finish of the season \u2013 even though we've run well at each event \u2013 and I think that will give us some momentum this weekend.\"<ref name=SIPreview/>\n\n==Practice and qualifying==\nThree practice sessions were held before the Sunday race\u2014one on Friday morning and two on Saturday morning. The first session lasted 120 minutes, and the second and third sessions 45 minutes.<ref name=\"event\">{{cite web|url=http://jayski.thatsracin.com/next/2003/2003darlington1.htm|title=The Race: Carolina Dodge Dealers 400|publisher=[[Jayski's Silly Season Site]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030618043626/http://jayski.thatsracin.com/next/2003/2003darlington1.htm|archive-date=June 18, 2003|accessdate=September 11, 2019}}</ref> In the first practice session, which was held in cool and overcast weather,<ref name=\"COQuali\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.thatsracin.com/mld/thatsracin/5394538.htm|title=Elliott Sadler wins pole for Sunday's main event|last=Poole|first=David|date=March 14, 2003|work=[[The Charlotte Observer]]|access-date=September 12, 2019|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040306091259/http://www.thatsracin.com/mld/thatsracin/5394538.htm|archive-date=March 6, 2004}}</ref> [[Elliott Sadler]] was fastest with a lap of 29.125 seconds. He was followed by Labonte, [[Ryan Newman (racing driver)|Ryan Newman]], Gordon, [[Kurt Busch]], [[Kenny Wallace]], Earnhardt, [[Rusty Wallace]], [[Mark Martin]] and [[Dave Blaney]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nascar.com/races/wc/2003/5/data/practice1_speeds.html|title=Practice 1 Speeds: Carolina Dodge Dealers 400|date=March 2003|publisher=NASCAR|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030320014201/http://www.nascar.com/races/wc/2003/5/data/practice1_speeds.html|archive-date=March 20, 2003|access-date=September 12, 2019}}</ref>[[File:ElliottSadlerAugust2007.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Elliott Sadler]] ''(pictured in 2007)'' took the first [[pole position]] of his career]]\n\nForty-three drivers attempted to qualify on Friday afternoon;<ref name=\"event\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nascar.com/races/wc/2003/5/data/entry_list.html|title=Entry List: Carolina Dodge Dealers 400|date=March 2003|publisher=NASCAR|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030315102236/http://www.nascar.com/races/wc/2003/5/data/entry_list.html|archive-date=March 15, 2003|access-date=September 12, 2019}}</ref> the maximum number allowed to race under NASCAR's [[Go or Go Home|qualifying procedure]]. Each driver ran two timed laps to determine pole position to 36th.<ref name=\"event\" /> The remainder of the field qualified through the use of provisionals; six were given to teams based on their 2002 [[NASCAR Cup Series#Owners' Championship|Owners Championship]] placing and the seventh was reserved for a former champion who did not qualify for the event or the next squad in the Owners' standings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jayski.com/stats/2003/2003prov.htm|title=2003 Winston Cup Provisional Page and Owners Points|date=May 12, 2003|publisher=Jayski's Silly Season Site|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050204083118/http://www.jayski.com/stats/2003/2003prov.htm|archive-date=February 4, 2005|access-date=December 4, 2019}}</ref> In his 146th race start, Sadler was the 16th driver on the track,<ref name=\"TSQuali\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.thestate.com/mld/thestate/sports/5400889.htm|title=Uncomfortable, but fast; Sadler claims pole for Sunday\u2019s race by winning the game of inches at Darlington|last=McLaurin|first=Jim|date=March 15, 2003|work=[[The State (newspaper)|The State]]|access-date=September 12, 2019|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040225155808/http://www.thestate.com/mld/thestate/sports/5400889.htm|archive-date=February 25, 2004}}</ref> and took the first [[pole position]] of his career with a lap of 28.902 seconds.<ref name=\"CrashQuali\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.crash.net/nascar/news/87268/1/sadler-claims-maiden-pole|title=Sadler claims maiden pole|date=March 14, 2003|publisher=Crash|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200101184032/https://www.crash.net/nascar/news/87268/1/sadler-claims-maiden-pole|archive-date=January 1, 2020|access-date=September 12, 2019}}</ref> He was joined on the [[Glossary of motorsport terms#G|grid]]'s front row by Newman, who stated he could have bettered Sadler's lap had he not ran wide in turns one and two.<ref name=\"TSQuali\" /> [[Jerry Nadeau]] qualified third, [[Jimmy Spencer]] fourth, and Gordon fifth. Busch had the pole position until Sadler's lap, and subsequent improvements from other competitors later in the session demoted him to sixth.<ref name=\"CrashQuali\" /> [[Ward Burton]] took seventh in the final minutes of qualifying.<ref name=\"CrashQuali\" /> Marlin, eighth, altered the [[Racing setup|setup of his car]] to increase its handling stability.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.al.com/motorsports/birminghamnews/index.ssf?/xml/story.ssf/html_standard.xsl?/base/sports/1047810190139020.xml|title=Eighth is enough|last=Sims|first=Neal|date=March 16, 2003|work=[[The Birmingham News]]|access-date=September 12, 2019|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030422113238/http://www.al.com/motorsports/birminghamnews/index.ssf?%2Fxml%2Fstory.ssf%2Fhtml_standard.xsl%3F%2Fbase%2Fsports%2F1047810190139020.xml|archive-date=April 22, 2003}}</ref> Waltrip and [[Todd Bodine]] were ninth and tenth.<ref name=\"CrashQuali\" /> 37th to 43rd placed-qualifiers Jeff Burton, [[Joe Nemechek]], [[Ricky Rudd]], [[Kyle Petty]], [[Tony Raines]], [[Larry Foyt]], and [[Brett Bodine]] used provisionals to enter the race.<ref name=\"COQuali\" /> After qualifying Sadler said, \"To get one this early and get it off our shoulders, you don't understand how big a relief this is and the weight that's been taken off my shoulders.\"<ref name=\"COQuali\" />\n\nOn Saturday morning Nadeau was quickest in the second practice session at 29.496 seconds, ahead of Johnson, [[Bill Elliott]], Stewart, Kenseth, [[Greg Biffle]], Nemechek, Martin, Harvick, and Gordon.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nascar.com/races/wc/2003/5/data/practice2_speeds.html|title=Practice 2 Speeds: Carolina Dodge Dealers 400|date=March 2003|publisher=NASCAR|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030320014037/http://www.nascar.com/races/wc/2003/5/data/practice2_speeds.html|archive-date=March 20, 2003|access-date=September 12, 2019}}</ref> During the session, Busch's engine failed on a slow lap; his team changed engines,<ref name=RTDFP23>{{Cite news|url=http://timesdispatch.com/sports/auto/MGBK9ELDCDD.html|title=NASCAR Notes|last=Ryan|first=Nate|date=March 16, 2003|work=[[Richmond Times-Dispatch]]|access-date=September 12, 2019|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030401233733/http://timesdispatch.com/sports/auto/MGBK9ELDCDD.html|archive-date=April 1, 2003}}</ref> which limited his on-track familiarisation.<ref name=\"NASCAROralRace\" /> Kenseth's car emitted smoke due to an unsecured oil line, which his mechanics repaired.<ref name=FordFPSat>{{cite press release|title=RR Troubles II: Kenseth Cured, Busch Blown|url=http://www.fordracing.com/news/?article=21679&flashcheck=1|url-status=dead|publisher=Ford Racing|date=March 15, 2003|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030413113349/http://www.fordracing.com/news/?article=21679&flashcheck=1|archive-date=April 13, 2003|access-date=September 12, 2019}}</ref> Later that day, Kenseth led the final practice session with a lap of 29.379 seconds; Johnson duplicated his second-practice result in second and Gordon improved from tenth to third. Nemechek, [[Jeff Green (racing driver)|Jeff Green]], Newman, Marlin, Kenny Wallace, Martin and Stewart made up positions four to ten.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nascar.com/races/wc/2003/5/data/practice3_speeds.html|title=Practice 3 Speeds: Carolina Dodge Dealers 400|date=March 2003|publisher=NASCAR|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030320014221/http://www.nascar.com/races/wc/2003/5/data/practice3_speeds.html|archive-date=March 20, 2003|access-date=September 12, 2019}}</ref> Towards the conclusion of the session, the right side of Waltrip's vehicle struck an outside barrier at turn two due to a cut tire, and he switched to a back-up car.<ref name=RTDFP23/><ref name=FordFPSat/>\n\n===Qualifying results===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n|+ Qualifying results\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Grid\n! scope=\"col\" |{{Abbr|Car|Car number}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Driver\n! scope=\"col\" | Team\n! scope=\"col\" | Manufacturer\n! scope=\"col\" | {{Tooltip|Time|Time in seconds}}\n! scope=\"col\" | {{Tooltip|Speed|Speed in MPH}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |  1\n|38\n|{{Sortname|Elliott|Sadler}}||[[Yates Racing|Robert Yates Racing]]\n|[[Ford Motor Company|Ford]]\n|28.902\n|170.147\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |  2\n| 12||{{Sortname|Ryan|Newman|Ryan Newman (racing driver)}}\n|[[Team Penske|Penske Racing]]\n|[[Dodge]]\n|29.034\n|169.374\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |  3\n| 01||{{Sortname|Jerry|Nadeau}}\n|[[Ginn Racing|MB2 Motorsports]]\n|[[Pontiac]]\n|29.069\n|169.170\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |  4\n| 7||{{Sortname|Jimmy|Spencer}}||[[Ultra Motorsports]]\n|Dodge\n|29.083\n|169.089\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |  5\n|24\n|{{Sortname|Jeff|Gordon}}\n|[[Hendrick Motorsports]]\n|[[Chevrolet]]\n|29.086\n|169.071\n|-\n! s