 Racing\n| Dodge|| 288||67\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 33\n|5\n| 24||{{sortname|Jeff|Gordon|nolink=1}}\n|Hendrick Motorsports\n| Chevrolet|| 286||69{{smallsup|1}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 34\n|24\n| 41||{{sortname|Casey|Mears|nolink=1}}\n|Chip Ganassi Racing\n| Dodge||286\n|61\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 35\n| 3|| 01||{{Sortname|Jerry|Nadeau|nolink=1}}\n|MB2 Motorsports\n|Pontiac\n|286\n|58\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 36\n|33\n| 29||{{sortname|Kevin|Harvick|nolink=1}}\n|Richard Childress Racing\n| Chevrolet|| 283||55\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 37\n|20\n| 18||{{sortname|Bobby|Labonte|nolink=1}}\n|Joe Gibbs Racing\n| Chevrolet|| 240||52\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 38\n| 26|| 43||{{Sortname|John|Andretti|nolink=1}}\n|Petty Enterprises\n|Dodge\n| 187||49\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 39\n|8\n| 40||{{sortname|Sterling|Marlin|nolink=1}}\n|Chip Ganassi Racing\n| Dodge|| 145||46\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 40\n|34\n| 0||{{Sortname|Jack|Sprague|nolink=1}}\n|Haas CNC Racing\n| Pontiac|| 144||43\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 41\n| 41|| 74||{{sortname|Tony|Raines|nolink=1}}\n|BACE Motorsports\n| Chevrolet|| 60||40\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 42\n|37\n| 99||{{sortname|Jeff|Burton|nolink=1}}\n|Roush Racing\n| Ford|| 32||37\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 43\n| 10|| 54||{{sortname|Todd|Bodine|nolink=1}}\n|BelCar Motorsports\n|Ford\n| 22||34\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n| colspan=\"9\" | {{center|{{small|{{smallsup|1}} Includes five bonus points for leading a lap}}}}\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n| colspan=\"9\" | {{center|{{small|{{smallsup|2}} Includes ten bonus points for leading the most laps}}}}\n|- class=\"sortbottom\n|colspan=\"9\"|{{center|{{small|''Source:<ref name=RR400/><ref>{{cite web|title=2003 Nascar Cup Series Carolina Dodge Dealers 400|url=https://results.motorsportstats.com/results/2003-carolina-dodge-dealers-400/classification|publisher=Motorsport Stats|accessdate=January 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=NASCAR Winston Cup Series Race No. 5: Carolina Dodge Dealers 400: Darlington Raceway|url=http://jayski.thatsracin.com/stats/2003standings/mar16results.htm|publisher=Jayski's Silly Season SIte|accessdate=January 1, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030804233804/http://jayski.thatsracin.com/stats/2003standings/mar16results.htm|archivedate=August 4, 2003|url-status=dead}}</ref>''}}}}\n|}\n\n==Standings after the race==\n{{col-start}}\n{{col-2}}\n;Drivers' Championship standings\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Rank\n! scope=\"col\" | +/\u2013\n! scope=\"col\" | Driver\n! scope=\"col\" | Points\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1\n| align=\"left\" | [[File:1rightarrow.png|10px]]\n| {{sortname|Matt|Kenseth|nolink=1}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 760\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |  2\n| align=\"left\" | [[File:1rightarrow.png|10px]]\n| {{sortname|Tony|Stewart|nolink=1}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 703 (\u201357)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |  3\n| align=\"left\" | [[File:1rightarrow.png|10px]]\n| {{sortname|Michael|Waltrip|nolink=1}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 698 (\u201362)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |  4\n| align=\"left\" | [[File:1uparrow green.svg|10px]] 6\n| {{sortname|Dale|Earnhardt Jr.|nolink=1}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 634 (\u2013126)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |  5\n| align=\"left\" | [[File:1uparrow green.svg|10px]] 11\n| {{sortname|Ricky|Craven|nolink=1}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 617 (\u2013143)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |  6\n| align=\"left\" | [[File:1uparrow green.svg|10px]] 8\n| {{sortname|Kurt|Busch|nolink=1}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 617 (\u2013143)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |  7\n| align=\"left\" | [[File:1uparrow green.svg|10px]] 8\n| {{sortname|Dave|Blaney|nolink=1}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 603 (\u2013157)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |  8\n| align=\"left\" | [[File:1downarrow red.svg|10px]] 4\n| {{sortname|Jimmie|Johnson|nolink=1}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 601 (\u2013159)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |  9\n| align=\"left\" | [[File:1uparrow green.svg|10px]] 2\n| {{sortname|Joe|Nemechek|nolink=1}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 601 (\u2013159)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |  10\n| align=\"left\" | [[File:1uparrow green.svg|10px]] 9\n| {{sortname|Elliott|Sadler|nolink=1}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 575 (\u2013185)\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n|colspan=\"9\"|{{center|{{small|''Source:<ref name=RR400/><ref name=PreRacePoints/>''}}}}\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n[[File:Matt-kenseth-bristol-2009.jpg|thumb|right|upright|alt=A man in his late thirties wearing a blue-and-white baseball cap and black sunglasses along with a blue jacket with sponsors' logos.|[[Matt Kenseth]] ''(pictured in 2009)'' remained the points leader with 760 points, after finishing eighth in the race.]]\n\n;Manufacturers' Championship standings\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Rank\n! scope=\"col\" | +/\u2013\n! scope=\"col\" | Manufacturer\n! scope=\"col\" | Points\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |  1\n| align=\"left\" | [[File:1rightarrow.png|10px]]\n| Ford\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 36\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |  2\n| align=\"left\" | [[File:1rightarrow.png|10px]]\n| Chevrolet\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 31 (\u20135)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |  3\n| align=\"left\" | [[File:1uparrow green.svg|10px]] 1\n| Pontiac\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 24 (\u201312)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |  4\n| align=\"left\" | [[File:1downarrow red.svg|10px]] 1\n| Dodge\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 19 (\u201317)\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n|colspan=\"9\"|{{center|{{small|''Source:<ref name=Manufacturers/>''}}}} \n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=N}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20111005052821/http://www.driveraverages.com/nascar_stats/race.php?sked_id=2003005 Race Results and Standings]\n\n{{NASCAR next race|\n  Series        = Winston Cup Series|\n  Season        = 2003 |\n  Previous_race = [[2003 Bass Pro Shops MBNA 500]] |\n  Next_race     = [[2003 Food City 500]] |\n}}\n{{NASCAR on FOX}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:2003 in sports in South Carolina|Carolina Dodge Dealers 400]]\n[[Category:2003 NASCAR Winston Cup Series|Carolina Dodge Dealers 400]]\n[[Category:NASCAR races at Darlington Raceway]]\n[[Category:March 2003 sports events in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{NASCAR race season infobox\n| Type           = CUST\n| Description    = Race 5 of 36 in the [[2003 NASCAR Winston Cup Series]] season\n| Race Name      = Carolina Dodge Dealers 400\n| Details ref    = <ref name=\"event\"/><ref name=RR400>{{cite web|title=2003 Carolina Dodge Dealers 400|url=https://www.racing-reference.info/race/2003_Carolina_Dodge_Dealers_400/W|publisher=Racing-Reference|accessdate=September 11, 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171101071449/http://racing-reference.info/race/2003_Carolina_Dodge_Dealers_400/W|archive-date=November 1, 2017}}</ref>\n| Fulldate       = {{Start date|2003|March|16}}\n| Year           = 2003\n| Race_No        = 5\n| Season_No      = 36\n| Image          = 2003 Carolina Dodge Dealers 400 finish.jpg\n| Caption       = The [[photo finish]] between [[Ricky Craven]] and [[Kurt Busch]]\n| Official name  = Carolina Dodge Dealers 400\n| Location       = [[Darlington Raceway]], [[Darlington, South Carolina]]\n| Course_mi      = 1.366\n| Course_km      = 2.198\n| Distance_laps  = 293\n| Distance_mi    = 400.238\n| Distance_km    = 644.014\n| Avg            = {{convert|126.214|mph|abbr=on}}\n| Weather        = Temperatures reaching up to {{convert|64.4|F|C}}; wind speeds up to {{convert|11.1|mph|km/h}}<ref name=WeatherInfo>{{cite web|title=Weather Information for Darlington, South Carolina|url=http://www.almanac.com/weather/history/SC/Darlington/2003-03-16|publisher=[[Old Farmer's Almanac]]|accessdate=September 11, 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180108062356/https://www.almanac.com/weather/history/SC/Darlington/2003-03-16|archive-date=January 8, 2018}}</ref>\n| Pole_Driver    = [[Elliott Sadler]]\n| Pole_Team      = [[Yates Racing|Robert Yates Racing]]\n| Pole_Time  = 28.902\n| Most_Driver    = [[Dale Earnhardt Jr.]]\n| Most_Team      = [[Dale Earnhardt, Inc.]]\n| Most_laps      = 91\n| Car            = 32\n| First_Driver   = [[Ricky Craven]]\n| First_Team     = [[PPI Motorsports]]\n| Network        = [[Fox NASCAR|Fox Broadcasting Company]]\n| Announcers     = [[Mike Joy]], [[Darrell Waltrip]], [[Larry McReynolds]]\n| Ratings = {{Plainlist|\n* 5.9/15 (Final)\n* 5.5/13 (Overnight)<ref>{{cite web|title=2003 NASCAR Winston Cup Series TV Ratings|url=http://www.jayski.com/pages/tvratings2003.htm|publisher=Jayski's Silly Season Site|accessdate=December 22, 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050207192126/http://www.jayski.com/pages/tvratings2003.htm|archivedate=February 7, 2005}}</ref>}}\n| Radio          = [[Motor Racing Network]]\n| Booth_Ann      = Joe Moore and [[Barney Hall]]\n| Turn_Ann       = [[Dave Moody]] (1 & 2) and [[Mike Bagley]] (3 & 4)\n|Course=|Attendance=55,000}}\n\nThe '''2003 Carolina Dodge Dealers 400''' was the fifth [[Stock car racing|stock car race]] of the [[2003 NASCAR Winston Cup Series]]. It was held on March 16, 2003, before a crowd of 55,000, in [[Darlington, South Carolina]], at [[Darlington Raceway]]. The 293-lap race, the 100th NASCAR Cup Series event at Darlington Raceway, was won by [[PPI Motorsports]] driver [[Ricky Craven]] after he started from the 31st position. [[Kurt Busch]] of the [[Roush Fenway Racing|Roush Racing]] squad finished in second place and [[Dave Blaney]] third for the [[Jasper Motorsports]] team.\n\n[[Elliott Sadler]] won the pole position by recording the fastest lap in qualifying. He and [[Ryan Newman (racing driver)|Ryan Newman]] traded the lead for the first two laps. [[Dale Earnhardt Jr.]] assumed the lead on lap 17 and went on to lead for 91 laps, more than any other driver. On lap 197, [[Jeff Gordon]] led at a [[Rolling start|rolling restart]] after a [[Racing flags#Yellow flag|yellow caution flag]], ahead of Sadler. Busch passed Gordon on the 269th lap but later had a [[power steering]] failure, allowing Craven to gradually lower his lead. By lap 291, Craven drew close enough to challenge Busch; after two attempts at a pass failed, he overtook Busch on the final lap, and won by two-thousands of a second, tied for the closest finish in series history.\n\nIt was Craven's second win of his career. The result advanced him from sixteenth to fifth in the [[List of NASCAR Sprint Cup Series champions|Drivers' Championship]], 143 [[List of NASCAR points scoring systems|points]] behind [[Matt Kenseth]], whose eighth-place finished  maintained his championship lead over [[Tony Stewart]]. [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]] maintained its lead in the [[List of NASCAR Manufacturers' champions|Manufacturers' Championship]], five points ahead of [[Chevrolet]] in second. [[Pontiac]] overtook [[Dodge]] for third with 31 races remaining in the season.\n\n==Background==\n[[File:DarlingtonRacewayDodgeCharger500.JPG|left|thumb|[[Darlington Raceway]] ''(pictured in 2008)'', where the race was held.]]\nThe 2003 Carolina Dodge Dealers 400 was the 5th of the 36 [[Stock car racing|stock car races]] in the [[2003 NASCAR Winston Cup Series]]. It was held on March 16, 2003, in [[Darlington, South Carolina]], at [[Darlington Raceway]],<ref name=\"RR400\" />  an [[Oval track racing|intermediate oval track]] which began hosting NASCAR races in the [[1950 NASCAR Grand National Series|1950 Grand National Series]];<ref name=DarlingtonTrack>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=4UC_C-0PQzoC&pg=PA10&lpg=PA10&dq=Darlington+Raceway+1950+intermediate+NASCAR&source=bl&ots=bn_ltdhDJo&sig=ACfU3U1RRr3cPVdtDXBYLTHx16vaW3YQMw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiE6PXay8rkAhVeQEEAHa4UCoIQ6AEwGnoECAsQAQ#v=onepage&q=Darlington%20Raceway%201950%20intermediate%20NASCAR&f=false|title=The Greatest NASCAR Tracks|last=Robinson|first=Matthew|publisher=[[Rosen Publishing]]|date=15 January 2005|isbn=978-1-4042-1400-2|location=New York City, United States|pages=10|access-date=September 12, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and was the 100th Cup Series race held at the track.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.indystar.com/print/articles/3/028832-3923-036.html|title=Darlington's 100th race may be its last in spring|last=Ballard|first=Steve|date=March 14, 2003|work=[[Indianapolis Star]]|access-date=September 12, 2019|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030314212215/http://www.indystar.com/print/articles/3/028832-3923-036.html|archive-date=March 14, 2003}}</ref> The track is a four-turn {{convert|1.366|mi|km|abbr=on}} egg-shaped superspeedway.<ref name=DarlingtonTrack/> Its first two turns are [[Banked turn|banked]] at 25 [[Degree (angle)|degrees]], while the final two turns are banked at 23 degrees. The [[Straight (racing)|frontstretch]] (the location of the finish line) and the backstretch are banked at three and two degrees, respectively.<ref name=\"darlingtontrackinfo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/jayski/tracks/story/_/id/18670465/darlington-raceway|title=Darlington Raceway|publisher=[[ESPN]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170628000656/http://www.espn.co.uk/jayski/tracks/story/_/id/18670465/darlington-raceway|archivedate=June 28, 2017|accessdate=January 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\nBefore the race, [[Matt Kenseth]] led the [[List of Monster Energy NASCAR Cup Series champions|Drivers' Championship]] with 618 [[List of NASCAR points scoring systems|points]], and [[Tony Stewart]] followed with 569 points. [[Michael Waltrip]] and [[Jimmie Johnson]] were third and fourth with 543 and 519 points respectively, ahead of [[Bobby Labonte]] in fifth with 510 points. [[Johnny Benson Jr.]], [[Kevin Harvick]], [[Jeff Gordon]], [[Jeff Burton]] and [[Dale Earnhardt Jr.]] rounded out the top ten.<ref name=PreRacePoints>{{cite web|url=http://jayski.com/stats/2003standings/mar9.htm|title=Drivers' Championship Classification After Atlanta|publisher=Jayski's Silly Season Site|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050307164708/http://jayski.com/stats/2003standings/mar9.htm|archivedate=March 7, 2005|accessdate=January 21, 2015}}</ref> In the [[List of NASCAR Manufacturers' champions|Manufacturers' Championship]], [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]] led with a total of 30 points, three points ahead of [[Chevrolet]] in second position. [[Dodge]], with 16 points, were one point ahead of [[Pontiac]] in third position.<ref name=Manufacturers>{{cite web|url=http://www.jayski.com/stats/2003/manu2003.htm|title=Manufacturers' Championship Classification|publisher=Jayski's Silly Season Site|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050204084345/http://www.jayski.com/stats/2003/manu2003.htm|archive-date=February 4, 2005|accessdate=January 21, 2015}}</ref> [[Sterling Marlin]] was the race's defending champion.<ref name=SIPreview>{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/motorsports/news/2003/03/12/glance_darlington_ap/|title='Still too tough to tame': Gordon looks to maintain momentum at Darlington|last=Austin|first=Chad|date=March 13, 2003|website=[[Sports Illustrated]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030422123139/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/motorsports/news/2003/03/12/glance_darlington_ap/|archive-date=April 22, 2003|accessdate=September 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDarlington Raceway had a highly abrasive track surface, which was heavily used and altered the complex of racing there. Drivers were required to strenuously monitor their tire degradation, and track position was the most important aspect due to the difficulty of on-circuit overtaking.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/rpm/wc/2003/0313/1522990.html|title=Difficult Darlington full of history|last=Massaro|first=Mike|date=March 13, 2003|publisher=ESPN|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030628114234/http://espn.go.com/rpm/wc/2003/0313/1522990.html|archive-date=June 28, 2003|access-date=September 12, 2019}}</ref> Gordon, who arrived as a favourite to win at Darlington Raceway due to his record six Cup Series victories there,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://foxsports.lycos.com/content/view?contentId=953444|title=Fox Watch: Five who thrive at Darlington|last=Behrendt|first=Todd|date=March 12, 2003|publisher=[[Fox Sports (United States)|Fox Sports]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030428233131/http://foxsports.lycos.com/content/view?contentId=953444|archive-date=April 28, 2003|access-date=September 12, 2019}}</ref> expressed a desire to continue his good form at the track: \"We didn't win in Atlanta, but we led laps and battled hard for the win. That was our first good finish of the season \u2013 even though we've run well at each event \u2013 and I think that will give us some momentum this weekend.\"<ref name=SIPreview/>\n\n==Practice and qualifying==\nThree practice sessions were held before the Sunday race\u2014one on Friday morning and two on Saturday morning. The first session lasted 120 minutes, and the second and third sessions 45 minutes.<ref name=\"event\">{{cite web|url=http://jayski.thatsracin.com/next/2003/2003darlington1.htm|title=The Race: Carolina Dodge Dealers 400|publisher=[[Jayski's Silly Season Site]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030618043626/http://jayski.thatsracin.com/next/2003/2003darlington1.htm|archive-date=June 18, 2003|accessdate=September 11, 2019}}</ref> In the first practice session, which was held in cool and overcast weather,<ref name=\"COQuali\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.thatsracin.com/mld/thatsracin/5394538.htm|title=Elliott Sadler wins pole for Sunday's main event|last=Poole|first=David|date=March 14, 2003|work=[[The Charlotte Observer]]|access-date=September 12, 2019|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040306091259/http://www.thatsracin.com/mld/thatsracin/5394538.htm|archive-date=March 6, 2004}}</ref> [[Elliott Sadler]] was fastest with a lap of 29.125 seconds. He was followed by Labonte, [[Ryan Newman (racing driver)|Ryan Newman]], Gordon, [[Kurt Busch]], [[Kenny Wallace]], Earnhardt, [[Rusty Wallace]], [[Mark Martin]] and [[Dave Blaney]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nascar.com/races/wc/2003/5/data/practice1_speeds.html|title=Practice 1 Speeds: Carolina Dodge Dealers 400|date=March 2003|publisher=NASCAR|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030320014201/http://www.nascar.com/races/wc/2003/5/data/practice1_speeds.html|archive-date=March 20, 2003|access-date=September 12, 2019}}</ref>[[File:ElliottSadlerAugust2007.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Elliott Sadler]] ''(pictured in 2007)'' took the first [[pole position]] of his career]]\n\nForty-three drivers attempted to qualify on Friday afternoon;<ref name=\"event\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nascar.com/races/wc/2003/5/data/entry_list.html|title=Entry List: Carolina Dodge Dealers 400|date=March 2003|publisher=NASCAR|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030315102236/http://www.nascar.com/races/wc/2003/5/data/entry_list.html|archive-date=March 15, 2003|access-date=September 12, 2019}}</ref> the maximum number allowed to race under NASCAR's [[Go or Go Home|qualifying procedure]]. Each driver ran two timed laps to determine pole position to 36th.<ref name=\"event\" /> The remainder of the field qualified through the use of provisionals; six were given to teams based on their 2002 [[NASCAR Cup Series#Owners' Championship|Owners Championship]] placing and the seventh was reserved for a former champion who did not qualify for the event or the next squad in the Owners' standings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jayski.com/stats/2003/2003prov.htm|title=2003 Winston Cup Provisional Page and Owners Points|date=May 12, 2003|publisher=Jayski's Silly Season Site|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050204083118/http://www.jayski.com/stats/2003/2003prov.htm|archive-date=February 4, 2005|access-date=December 4, 2019}}</ref> In his 146th race start, Sadler was the 16th driver on the track,<ref name=\"TSQuali\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.thestate.com/mld/thestate/sports/5400889.htm|title=Uncomfortable, but fast; Sadler claims pole for Sunday\u2019s race by winning the game of inches at Darlington|last=McLaurin|first=Jim|date=March 15, 2003|work=[[The State (newspaper)|The State]]|access-date=September 12, 2019|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040225155808/http://www.thestate.com/mld/thestate/sports/5400889.htm|archive-date=February 25, 2004}}</ref> and took the first [[pole position]] of his career with a lap of 28.902 seconds.<ref name=\"CrashQuali\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.crash.net/nascar/news/87268/1/sadler-claims-maiden-pole|title=Sadler claims maiden pole|date=March 14, 2003|publisher=Crash|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200101184032/https://www.crash.net/nascar/news/87268/1/sadler-claims-maiden-pole|archive-date=January 1, 2020|access-date=September 12, 2019}}</ref> He was joined on the [[Glossary of motorsport terms#G|grid]]'s front row by Newman, who stated he could have bettered Sadler's lap had he not ran wide in turns one and two.<ref name=\"TSQuali\" /> [[Jerry Nadeau]] qualified third, [[Jimmy Spencer]] fourth, and Gordon fifth. Busch had the pole position until Sadler's lap, and subsequent improvements from other competitors later in the session demoted him to sixth.<ref name=\"CrashQuali\" /> [[Ward Burton]] took seventh in the final minutes of qualifying.<ref name=\"CrashQuali\" /> Marlin, eighth, altered the [[Racing setup|setup of his car]] to increase its handling stability.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.al.com/motorsports/birminghamnews/index.ssf?/xml/story.ssf/html_standard.xsl?/base/sports/1047810190139020.xml|title=Eighth is enough|last=Sims|first=Neal|date=March 16, 2003|work=[[The Birmingham News]]|access-date=September 12, 2019|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030422113238/http://www.al.com/motorsports/birminghamnews/index.ssf?%2Fxml%2Fstory.ssf%2Fhtml_standard.xsl%3F%2Fbase%2Fsports%2F1047810190139020.xml|archive-date=April 22, 2003}}</ref> Waltrip and [[Todd Bodine]] were ninth and tenth.<ref name=\"CrashQuali\" /> 37th to 43rd placed-qualifiers Jeff Burton, [[Joe Nemechek]], [[Ricky Rudd]], [[Kyle Petty]], [[Tony Raines]], [[Larry Foyt]], and [[Brett Bodine]] used provisionals to enter the race.<ref name=\"COQuali\" /> After qualifying Sadler said, \"To get one this early and get it off our shoulders, you don't understand how big a relief this is and the weight that's been taken off my shoulders.\"<ref name=\"COQuali\" />\n\nOn Saturday morning Nadeau was quickest in the second practice session at 29.496 seconds, ahead of Johnson, [[Bill Elliott]], Stewart, Kenseth, [[Greg Biffle]], Nemechek, Martin, Harvick, and Gordon.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nascar.com/races/wc/2003/5/data/practice2_speeds.html|title=Practice 2 Speeds: Carolina Dodge Dealers 400|date=March 2003|publisher=NASCAR|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030320014037/http://www.nascar.com/races/wc/2003/5/data/practice2_speeds.html|archive-date=March 20, 2003|access-date=September 12, 2019}}</ref> During the session, Busch's engine failed on a slow lap; his team changed engines,<ref name=RTDFP23>{{Cite news|url=http://timesdispatch.com/sports/auto/MGBK9ELDCDD.html|title=NASCAR Notes|last=Ryan|first=Nate|date=March 16, 2003|work=[[Richmond Times-Dispatch]]|access-date=September 12, 2019|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030401233733/http://timesdispatch.com/sports/auto/MGBK9ELDCDD.html|archive-date=April 1, 2003}}</ref> which limited his on-track familiarisation.<ref name=\"NASCAROralRace\" /> Kenseth's car emitted smoke due to an unsecured oil line, which his mechanics repaired.<ref name=FordFPSat>{{cite press release|title=RR Troubles II: Kenseth Cured, Busch Blown|url=http://www.fordracing.com/news/?article=21679&flashcheck=1|url-status=dead|publisher=Ford Racing|date=March 15, 2003|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030413113349/http://www.fordracing.com/news/?article=21679&flashcheck=1|archive-date=April 13, 2003|access-date=September 12, 2019}}</ref> Later that day, Kenseth led the final practice session with a lap of 29.379 seconds; Johnson duplicated his second-practice result in second and Gordon improved from tenth to third. Nemechek, [[Jeff Green (racing driver)|Jeff Green]], Newman, Marlin, Kenny Wallace, Martin and Stewart made up positions four to ten.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nascar.com/races/wc/2003/5/data/practice3_speeds.html|title=Practice 3 Speeds: Carolina Dodge Dealers 400|date=March 2003|publisher=NASCAR|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030320014221/http://www.nascar.com/races/wc/2003/5/data/practice3_speeds.html|archive-date=March 20, 2003|access-date=September 12, 2019}}</ref> Towards the conclusion of the session, the right side of Waltrip's vehicle struck an outside barrier at turn two due to a cut tire, and he switched to a back-up car.<ref name=RTDFP23/><ref name=FordFPSat/>\n\n===Qualifying results===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n|+ Qualifying results\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Grid\n! scope=\"col\" |{{Abbr|Car|Car number}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Driver\n! scope=\"col\" | Team\n! scope=\"col\" | Manufacturer\n! scope=\"col\" | {{Tooltip|Time|Time in seconds}}\n! scope=\"col\" | {{Tooltip|Speed|Speed in MPH}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |  1\n|38\n|{{Sortname|Elliott|Sadler}}||[[Yates Racing|Robert Yates Racing]]\n|[[Ford Motor Company|Ford]]\n|28.902\n|170.147\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |  2\n| 12||{{Sortname|Ryan|Newman|Ryan Newman (racing driver)}}\n|[[Team Penske|Penske Racing]]\n|[[Dodge]]\n|29.034\n|169.374\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |  3\n| 01||{{Sortname|Jerry|Nadeau}}\n|[[Ginn Racing|MB2 Motorsports]]\n|[[Pontiac]]\n|29.069\n|169.170\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |  4\n| 7||{{Sortname|Jimmy|Spencer}}||[[Ultra Motorsports]]\n|