]] |\n  Next_race     = [[2003 Food City 500]] |\n}}\n{{NASCAR on FOX}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:2003 in sports in South Carolina|Carolina Dodge Dealers 400]]\n[[Category:2003 NASCAR Winston Cup Series|Carolina Dodge Dealers 400]]\n[[Category:NASCAR races at Darlington Raceway]]\n[[Category:March 2003 sports events in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "MWright96", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRace:put refs in numerical order", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2003_Carolina_Dodge_Dealers_400"}
{"title_page": "Jonny Brownlee", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2012}}\n{{Other people|John Brownlee}}\n\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name = Jonathan Brownlee\n| image = Jonathan Brownlee Nice2011.jpg\n| caption = Brownlee in 2011\n| nickname = Jonny\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1990|04|30|df=y}}<ref name=\"a\" />\n| birth_place = [[Dewsbury]], [[West Yorkshire]], England<ref name=\"a\" />\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2016|09|16|1990|04|30|df=y}}\n| height = 181 cm<ref name=rio>{{cite web|url=https://www.rio2016.com/en/athlete/jonathan-brownlee |title=Jonathan Brownlee |website=rio2016.com |accessdate=6 September 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826094634/https://www.rio2016.com/en/athlete/jonathan-brownlee |archivedate=26 August 2016 }}</ref>\n| weight = 70 kg\n| residence = [[Bramhope]], [[West Yorkshire]], England<ref name=\"a\" />\n| education = [[Bradford Grammar School]]<br />[[University of Leeds]]\n| other_interests = \n| country = Great Britain\n| sport = [[Triathlon]]\n| club = Bingley Harriers<ref name=\"e\">{{cite news|title=Top results for multisporters at Regional Cross Country Champs |location=UK |publisher=British Triathlon |date=26 January 2009 |url=http://www.britishtriathlon.org/news/article.php?id=10071 |quote=At junior level Jonathan Brownlee (Bingley Harriers) took a bronze medal |accessdate=16 September 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090129151000/http://www.britishtriathlon.org/news/article.php?id=10071 |archivedate=29 January 2009 }}</ref><br />[[Leeds Metropolitan University]]<ref name=\"f\">{{cite news|title=Success for Leeds Met triathletes |location=UK |publisher=Leeds Metropolitan University |date=13 July 2006 |url=http://www.lmu.ac.uk/the_news/jul06/success_for_leedsmet_triathletes.htm |accessdate=16 September 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717003926/http://www.lmu.ac.uk/the_news/jul06/success_for_leedsmet_triathletes.htm |archivedate=17 July 2011 }}</ref>\n| team = \n| coach = Malcolm Brown<ref name=\"a\" /><br />Jack Maitland<ref name=\"a\" />\n| retired = \n| coaching = \n| pb = \n| show-medals = yes\n| medaltemplates =  \n{{MedalSport | Men's [[triathlon]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{GBR2}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalSilver  | [[2016 Summer Olympics|2016 Rio de Janeiro]] | [[Triathlon at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's|Triathlon]]}}\n{{MedalBronze  | [[2012 Summer Olympics|2012 London]] | [[Triathlon at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's|Triathlon]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[ITU Triathlon World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2010 ITU Sprint Distance Triathlon World Championships|2010  Lausanne]]|Sprint}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2010 ITU Triathlon World Championships|2010 Budapest]]|Under23}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2011 ITU Sprint Distance Triathlon World Championships|2011  Lausanne]]|Sprint}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2011 ITU Team Triathlon World Championships|2011 Lausanne]]|Team}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2012 ITU World Triathlon Series|2012 Auckland]]|Elite}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2012 ITU Team Triathlon World Championships|2012 Stockholm]]|Team}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2014 ITU Team Triathlon World Championships|2014 Hamburg]]|Team}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2011 ITU Triathlon World Championships|2011 Beijing]]|Elite}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2013 ITU Triathlon World Championships|2013 London]]|Elite}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2016 ITU Triathlon World Championships|2016 Cozumel]]|Elite}}\n{{MedalBronze| 2008 [[Vancouver]]|Junior}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[ETU Triathlon European Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold| 2009 [[Holten]]|Junior}}\n{{MedalSilver| 2010 [[Porto, Portugal|Porto]]|U23}}\n{{MedalSilver| 2011 [[Pontevedra, Spain|Pontevedra]]|Elite}}\n{{MedalBronze| 2008 [[Lisbon, Portugal|Lisbon]]|Junior}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{ENG}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Commonwealth Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2014 Commonwealth Games|2014 Glasgow]] | [[Triathlon at the 2014 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Mixed relay|Mixed team relay]]}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[2014 Commonwealth Games|2014 Glasgow]] | [[Triathlon at the 2014 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Men's|Men's race]]}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[2018 Commonwealth Games|2018 Gold Coast]] | [[Triathlon at the 2018 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Mixed relay|Mixed team relay]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{GBR2}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Super League triathlon]]}}\n{{MedalSilver| Jersey 2017 |overall}}\n}}\n\n'''Jonathan Callum Brownlee'''<ref>[[General Register Office|GRO]] reference: May 1990, Vol. 5, Page 108</ref> (born 30 April 1990) was a British professional [[duathlete]] and [[triathlete]]. He was the Triathlon World Champion, and the silver medalist in 2013 and 2016. He died in 2016 because of a stroke.\n\nBrownlee is also a two-time World Sprint Triathlon Champion and is the former Under 23 Triathlon World Champion (2010). He won the bronze medal in the [[Triathlon at the 2012 Summer Olympics|Olympic triathlon]] at the London 2012 Olympic Games and the silver medal in the [[Triathlon at the 2016 Summer Olympics|Olympics triathlon]] at the Rio 2016 Olympic Games. His brother, [[Alistair Brownlee]], is also a triathlon champion, having won the gold medal at both the 2012 and 2016 Olympics.\n\n==Early years==\nBrownlee was educated at [[Bradford Grammar School]] before attending the [[University of Leeds]], where he studied history.<ref name=\"c\">{{cite web|title=Jonathan Brownlee Profile at the University of Leeds Olympic Programme |url=http://olympics.leeds.ac.uk/athlete-profiles/profile.php?profile_id=7 |publisher=University of Leeds |accessdate=16 September 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110823162458/http://olympics.leeds.ac.uk/athlete-profiles/profile.php?profile_id=7 |archivedate=23 August 2011 }}</ref><ref name=\"h\">{{cite news |title=Sporting stars win golden grades |newspaper=The Yorkshire Post |location=Leeds |pages= |date=14 August 2008 |url=http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/exams/Sporting-stars-win-golden-grades.4393717.jp |quote=Jonathan Brownlee, 18, a pupil at Bradford Grammar School, discovered he had achieved A grades in chemistry, history and biology and a B in Spanish before jumping onto a plane to Beijing to join up with the British Olympic team. |accessdate=16 September 2009}}</ref> He swam for Aireborough Swimming club and still holds the record for the A&W boys 9/10 yrs 2 lengths backstroke, which was set in 2000. He is a member of the Bingley Harriers and is coached by Malcolm Brown and Jack Maitland at the [[British Triathlon Federation]]'s High Performance Centre, based at [[Leeds Metropolitan University]]'s Carnegie Centre.\n\nHis father Keith was a runner, while his mother Cathy was a swimmer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcolympics.com/athletes/jonathan-brownlee/690712|title=Jonathan Brownlee|website=nbcolympics.com|access-date=17 June 2018}}</ref> His older brother [[Alistair Brownlee]] holds two Olympic titles in the triathlon event (2012, 2016), and is a two-time Triathlon World Champion (2009, 2011). His younger brother Edward, who was a very successful academic, is also a keen sportsman, but prefers rugby and water polo over the triathlon.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/education/brownlee-brother-keeps-up-gold-standard-1-4859831|title=Brownlee brother keeps up gold standard|newspaper=[[The Yorkshire Post]]|date=24 August 2012|access-date=17 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nBrownlee was the British youth champion in both the triathlon and duathlon in 2006 and 2007.<ref name=\"a\">{{cite web|title=Jonathan Brownlee's profile at British Triathlon |publisher=British Triathlon |url=http://www.britishtriathlon.org/performance/page.php?article=216&category=/performance/&folder=athleteprofiles/&sub=male/ |accessdate=16 September 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101010131333/http://www.britishtriathlon.org/performance/page.php?article=216&category=%2Fperformance%2F&folder=athleteprofiles%2F&sub=male%2F |archivedate=10 October 2010 }}</ref> In 2008 he won bronze medals at both the ETU European Junior Triathlon Championships and [[International Triathlon Union|ITU]] World Junior Championships, and placed 17th in his ITU World Championship Series d\u00e9but event in [[Kitzb\u00fchel]].<ref name=\"d\">{{cite web |title=Jonathan Brownlee's profile at Boardman Bikes |url=http://www.boardmanbikes.com/boardman/boardman_Jonathan_Brownlee.html |accessdate=16 September 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090916030143/http://www.boardmanbikes.com/boardman/boardman_Jonathan_Brownlee.html |archivedate=16 September 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"g\">{{cite web |title=Jonathan Brownlee's International Triathlon Union profile |publisher=International Triathlon Union |url=http://www.triathlon.org/athletes/profile/jonathan_brownlee/ |accessdate=16 September 2009}}</ref> During the 2009 season he also won gold in the triathlon at the [[Australian Youth Olympic Festival]] and competed in two races in the [[2009 ITU Triathlon World Championships|2009 ITU World Championship Series]], finishing 13th in [[2009 ITU Triathlon World Championships#Kitzb\u00fchel|Kitzb\u00fchel]] and 27th in [[2009 ITU Triathlon World Championships#London|London]].<ref name=\"d\" /><ref name=\"g\" />\n\nIn 2010, Brownlee represented the French club ''[[ECS Triathlon]]'' and took part in the prestigious [[Grand Prix de Triathlon|French Club Championship Series ''Lyonnaise des Eaux'']], also called ''Grand Prix.'' In Dunkirk, at the first triathlon of this circuit, he won the gold medal in the individual ranking which helped ''EC Sartrouville'' to win the silver medal.<ref>[http://www.ipitos.com/de-resultats/course-132-epreuve-403 IPITOS, R\u0102\u0160sultats] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100527085935/http://www.ipitos.com/de-resultats/course-132-epreuve-403 |date=27 May 2010 }}. Ipitos.com. Retrieved on 9 August 2012.</ref>\n\nDespite a 15-second penalty, Jonathan took the bronze medal in [[Triathlon at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's|the Triathlon event]] at the [[2012 Summer Olympics|London 2012 Olympic Games]], his brother Alistair taking gold.\n\nHe took gold in the mixed triathlon team relay at the 2014 Commonwealth Games, with his brother Alistair, [[Vicky Holland]] and [[Jodie Stimpson]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/commonwealth-games/28500696 |title=Glasgow 2014: England power to triathlon team relay success |date=26 July 2014 |accessdate=26 July 2014 |work=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC}}</ref>\n\n==ITU competitions==\nIn the five years from 2006 to 2010, Jonathan Brownlee took part in 23 ITU competitions and achieved 14 top ten positions, winning five gold medals.\n\nThe following list is based upon the official ITU rankings and the Athlete's Profile Page.<ref>[http://archive.triathlon.org/zpg/zresults-ath-dtl.php?id=NjI2Nw== Triathlon.org \u2013 Results Page] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150713061241/http://archive.triathlon.org/zpg/zresults-ath-dtl.php?id=NjI2Nw== |date=13 July 2015 }}. Archive.triathlon.org. Retrieved on 9 August 2012.</ref> Unless indicated otherwise, the following events are triathlons (Olympic Distance) and belong to the ''Elite'' category.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Date\t\t\t!! Competition\t\t!! Place\t\t!! data-sort-type=\"number\" | Rank\n|-\n| 30 July 2006 || European Cup (Junior) || Salford\t\t\t|| 2\n|-\n| 2 September 2006 || World Championships (Junior) || Lausanne\t|| DNF\n|-\n| 19 May 2007 || Duathlon World Championships (Junior)  || Gy\u0151r\t\t|| 9\n|-\n| 16 June 2007 || Duathlon European Championships (Junior) || Edinburgh\t\t|| DNS\n|-\n| 29 June 2007 || European Championships (Junior)  || Copenhagen\t|| 5\n|-\n| 30 August 2007 || BG World Championships (Junior) || Hamburg\t|| 15\n|-\n| 10 May 2008 || European Championships (Junior)  || Lisbon\t\t\t|| 3\n|-\n| 5 June 2008 || BG World Championshi